{"title_page": "Pioneer Square South and Pioneer Square North stations", "text_new": "{{About-distinguish2|the light rail stations in Portland, Oregon|[[Pioneer Square station]] in Seattle}}\n{{Infobox Station\n | name          = {{MAX infobox header|Pioneer Square South|blue|red}}{{MAX infobox header|Pioneer Square North|blue|red}}\n | type          = [[MAX Light Rail]] stations\n | image         = Pioneer Square South MAX station.jpg\n | image_caption = The platform of Pioneer Square South station in 2009\n | address       = [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]]<br/>[[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]], U.S.\n | country       =\n | line          = {{TMTC bullet|blue|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Blue Line|Blue Line]]{{br}}{{TMTC bullet|red|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Red Line|Red Line]]\n | coordinates   = {{Coord|45|31|08|N|122|40|46|W|format=dms|display=inline,title|type:landmark_region:US-OR}}\n | connections   ={{rint|bus|1}}{{nbsp}}'''[[Portland Transit Mall]]'''{{br}}{{rint|tram|1}}{{nbsp}}'''[[MAX Light Rail]]''':{{Block indent|em=1|1=<nowiki />{{TMTC bullet|green|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Green Line|Green Line]]{{br}}{{TMTC bullet|orange|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}{{TMTC bullet|yellow|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow Line]]{{br}}at [[Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th stations|Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th]]}}\n | platform      = 2 one-way [[side platform]]s\n | tracks        = 1 per split\n | parking       = \n | bicycle       = \n | baggage_check =\n | passengers    = 1,796 (Pioneer Square South){{br}}3,327 (Pioneer Square North){{br}}5,123 (total){{br}}weekday boardings (fall 2019)<ref name=\"pax-census-fall-2019\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/about/pdf/census/2019fall/max_station_passenger_census_report.pdf |title=TriMet MAX Light Rail Passenger Census \u2013 Fall 2019 |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310153349/https://trimet.org/about/pdf/census/2019fall/max_station_passenger_census_report.pdf |archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n | pass_year     =\n | pass_percent  =\n | pass_system   =\n | opened        = {{Start date|1986|09|05}}\n | closed        = \n | rebuilt       = \n | ADA           = yes\n | code          = \n | owned         = [[TriMet]]\n | services      ={{s-rail|title=TMTC}}\n{{s-text|text='''North'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|next=Morrison/SW 3rd|rows2=2|oneway2=yes}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|hide2=yes}}\n{{s-text|text='''South'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Library/SW 9th Ave|next=Yamhill District|rows1=2|oneway1=yes}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|next=Yamhill District|hide1=yes}}\n | other_services_collapsible=yes\n | other_services_header=Former services\n | other_services=\n{{s-rail|title=TMTC}}\n{{s-text|text='''North'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|next=Mall/SW 5th Ave|rows2=3|oneway2=yes|notemid=''1986\u20132020''|note2=(''closed'')}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|hide2=yes|notemid=''2004\u20132009''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Yellow|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|oneway2=yes|notemid=''2004\u20132009''|hide2=yes|type=2009}}\n{{s-text|text='''South'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Library/SW 9th Ave|next=Mall/SW 4th Ave|rows1=3|oneway1=yes|notemid=''1986\u20132020''|note2=(''closed'')}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|next=Mall/SW 4th Ave|hide1=yes|notemid=''2001\u20132020''|note2=(''closed'')}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Yellow|previous=Library/SW 9th Ave|next=Mall/SW 4th Ave|notemid=''2004\u20132009''|hide1=yes|oneway1=true|note2=(''closed'')}}\n | mpassengers   =\n}}\n'''Pioneer Square South''' and '''Pioneer Square North''' are a pair of [[light rail]] stations in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States, served by [[TriMet]] as part of its [[MAX Light Rail]] system. The platforms occupy the sidewalks of Southwest Yamhill and Morrison streets between Broadway and 6th Avenue in [[downtown Portland]], and are the 21st and 7th stops eastbound on the [[MAX Blue Line|Blue Line]] and the [[MAX Red Line|Red Line]], respectively. They are situated directly west of the [[Portland Transit Mall]] at [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]]; these stations, along with the [[Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th stations]] that are served by the [[MAX Green Line|Green]], [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]], and [[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow]] lines, mark the only [[Interchange station|transfer point]] in the MAX system where riders can board any of the five existing lines.\n\nThe Pioneer Square stations are among the 27 original stations built as part of the Banfield light rail project\u2014Portland's first light rail line. They opened along with the inaugural service of MAX on September 5, 1986. The Red Line began serving the stations in September 2001, initially connecting downtown to [[Portland International Airport]]. In 2003, the Red Line extended westward to [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]]. The Yellow Line also served the stations from 2004 to 2009, connecting downtown to the [[Portland Metropolitan Exposition Center|Expo Center]]; TriMet rerouted this line to serve the transit mall in August 2009.\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Pioneer Courthouse Square}}\n\nThe Portland city block bound by Southwest Morrison and Yamhill streets to the north and south, and 6th Avenue and Broadway to the east and west had previously been occupied by various structures, including a school, a hotel, and a parking garage. In March 1856, a proclamation created School District No. 1, which built the city's first permanent public school at this location.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://oregonhistoryproject.org/articles/historical-records/central-school/#.XnI3dKhKhhE |title=Central School |publisher=[[Oregon Historical Society]] |date=March 17, 2018 |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930101129/https://www.oregonhistoryproject.org/articles/historical-records/central-school/ |archive-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Referred to as Central School, it opened on May 7, 1858.<ref>{{cite news |last=Killen |first=John |title=Throwback Thursday: Portland public schools, started in 1850s, took awhile to catch on |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=June 11, 2015 |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/history/2015/06/throwback_thursday_portland_pu.html |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318151006/https://www.oregonlive.com/history/2015/06/throwback_thursday_portland_pu.html |archive-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> With the arrival of the [[Northern Pacific Railway]] to Portland in 1883, [[Henry Villard]] purchased the site of Central School for $75,000 and began building a first class hotel. The ensuing [[Panic of 1884]] halted construction for five years due to the collapse of Villard's finances. Construction resumed with the help of George B. Markle and other local investors, and the [[Portland Hotel]] opened on April 7, 1890. Over the next several decades, the Portland Hotel would establish itself as the city's social center and the \"place to see and be seen.\"<ref name=\"portland-hotel\">{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=The Portland Hotel: Once the place to see and be seen |date=April 2, 2011 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/O/2011/04/the_portland_hotel_once_the_pl.html |access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pioneer Square MAX station north - Portland, Oregon.JPG|thumb|left|The westbound platform on the north side of the square, 2011]]\n\n[[Meier & Frank]] purchased the Portland Hotel in 1944 and continued operating it until 1951, after which the company tore it down and built a parking garage in its place.<ref name=\"portland-hotel\"/><ref name=\"history-pioneer-photos\">{{cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/multimedia/2013/10/the_history_of_pioneer_courtho.html |last=Vattiat |first=Drew |title=The history of Pioneer Courthouse Square in photos |date=October 4, 2013 |newspaper=The Oregonian |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> In January 1969, Meier & Frank request a permit for the construction of an 11-story, 800-car parking garage, which the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|Portland City Council]] and the Portland Planning Commission rejected following a series of heated public hearings.<ref name=\"began\">{{cite book |last=Halprin |first=Lawrence |last2=Halprin |first2=Anna |title=Where the revolution began |editor=Gragg, Randy |publisher=Spacemaker Press |location=Washington, DC |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-9824392-1-0 |oclc= 449857189}}</ref> The controversial proposal led the local business community and the city to pursue a comprehensive downtown plan that envisioned turning the site into a public space instead.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thesquarepdx.org/history/ |title=History: Timeline |publisher=Pioneer Courthouse Square Administrative Office |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/multimedia/2013/10/history_of_pioneer_courthouse.html |last=Vattiat |first=Drew |title=History of Pioneer Courthouse Square: The winning design and four rejected finalists from 1980 (photos) |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=October 4, 2013 |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> After several negotiations between then-Mayor [[Neil Goldschmidt]] and Meier & Frank, the city purchased the property and in 1980, announced a national design competition for a plaza that would be called [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]].<ref name=\"history-pioneer-photos\"/>\n\nPortland's first light rail line, which planners referred to as the Banfield light rail project, received federal approval for construction in September 1980. Over a year later, TriMet published a conceptual design report of the project for the city that outlined a 27-station, {{convert|15.1|mi|km|1|adj=on}} line, including a pair of light rail stations at Pioneer Courthouse Square. The platforms would be situated along the north and south ends of the square on Southwest Morrison and Yamhill streets.<ref name=\"Conceptual Design\">{{cite report |author=Tri-County Metropolitan Transportation District of Oregon |title=Banfield Light Rail Project: Conceptual Design Information for the City of Portland |url=https://pdxscholar.library.pdx.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1008&context=oscdl_trimet |publisher=TriMet Collection |volume=9 |date=November 1, 1981 |access-date=July 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928184313/http://pdxscholar.library.pdx.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1008&context=oscdl_trimet |archivedate=September 28, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{rp|37\u201338}} Construction of the line commenced in April 1983 in Gresham and largely progressed from east to west,<ref>{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=Tri-Met opens bids on first light-rail track work |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 11, 1983 |page=B1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=Light-rail work gets go-ahead |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 31, 1983 |page=D16}}</ref> with the downtown segment among the final sections to be completed.<ref name=\"light-rails-jolly\">{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=Light rail's jolly trolley progress on track |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 4, 1986 |page=B5}}</ref> Street and sidewalk reconstruction work finally reached downtown in March 1984.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Light-rail work [photo and caption only] |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 10, 1984 |quote=Ralph L. Mowatt, a welder for Portland General Electric Co., cuts iron beam in street at Southwest First Avenue and Morrison Street on Friday as construction on the Banfield light-rail project moved downtown this week with utilities beginning to relocate lines. |page=C1}}</ref> While work continued on the line, the city finished building the square and dedicated it on April 6.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ritz |first=Richard E. |title=Flow of people will complete square's design |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 3, 1984 |page=B5}}</ref><ref name=\"soul\">{{cite news |last=Gragg |first=Randy |title=Pioneer Courthouse Square: Soul of the City\" (10th anniversary feature) |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 4, 1994 |pages=A1, A6}}</ref> By March 1986, major light rail construction work had ceased.<ref name=\"light-rails-jolly\"/> Line testing in downtown began with the arrival of the first light rail car the following May.<ref>{{cite news |last=Murphy |first=Bill |title=Downtown debut |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=May 9, 1986 |page=1 |quote=The first Tri-Met light-rail car to appear downtown is towed up Southwest Morrison Street Thursday. It will be open for public inspection at downtown locations for the next week.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Shoppers get first look at Tri-Met light-rail car |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=May 9, 1986 |page=D8}}</ref> \n\nOn September 5, 1986, TriMet officially opened the light rail line, which it named Metropolitan Area Express (MAX), to the public.<ref>{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=All aboard! MAX on track; ride free |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=September 5, 1986 |page=1}}</ref> A three-day celebration took place across the route, including at Pioneer Courthouse Square, which hosted an opening ceremony and several concerts.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Riding the Rails; Schedule of events: Sept. 5\u20137 |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=September 5, 1986 |page=T4}}</ref> More than 3,000 people gathered at the square to welcome the 11:45 am arrival of the first train from Gresham.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hayakawa |first=Alan R. |title=Whistle-stop tour inaugurates MAX light rail |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=September 6, 1986 |page=B6}}</ref> Between 1986 and 1998, only one MAX service that ran from [[Cleveland Avenue station|Cleveland Avenue]] in central Gresham to [[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|11th Avenue]] served the Pioneer Square stations. In 1998, TriMet extended this service farther west to [[Hatfield Government Center station|Hatfield Government Center]] in downtown Hillsboro with the opening of the Westside MAX. On September 10, 2001, the Red Line, which connected downtown\u2014and eventually [[Beaverton Transit Center|Beaverton]]\u2014to [[Portland International Airport station|Portland International Airport]] became the second line to serve the station.<ref name=\"oreg-2001-city-that-moves\">{{cite news|last1=Oliver|first1=Gordon|title=Portland now 'the city that moves', mayor says [opening of MAX Red Line]|newspaper=The Oregonian|date=September 11, 2001|page=1}}</ref><ref name=\"direct service Beaverton\">{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |date=August 27, 2003 |title=MAX fares increase, direct service from Beaverton to PDX starts |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D2}}</ref> From 2004 to 2009, the Yellow Line, which runs to the [[Expo Center station|Expo Center]] in North Portland, also stopped at this station until TriMet rerouted it to the new light rail tracks on Portland Transit Mall in August 2009.<ref name=\"tribune2009-0828\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New MAX line opens downtown |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=August 28, 2009 |url=http://pamplinmedia.com/component/content/article?id=54413 |access-date=May 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103091415/http://pamplinmedia.com/component/content/article?id=54413 |archive-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Station details==\n{{stack|float=right|[[File:Pioneer Courthouse Square - west half.jpg|thumb|Entrance to the visitor information center, which also houses TriMet's ticket office]]}}\n{|table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=70 rowspan=3 valign=top|'''Sidewalk{{br}}platform'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100 rowspan=2 valign=top| '''Westbound'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=530| \u2190 {{TMTC bullet|blue|size=5}} '''[[MAX Blue Line|Blue Line]]''' towards {{stn|Hatfield Government Center}} <small>([[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue]])</small>\n|-\n| \u2190 {{TMTC bullet|red|size=5}} '''[[MAX Red Line|Red Line]]''' towards [[Beaverton Transit Center]] <small>(Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue)</small>\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|<small>[[Side platform]], doors will open on the left</small>\n|-\n|colspan=3 align=center| [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]]\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" rowspan=3 valign=top|'''Sidewalk{{br}}platform'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|Side platform, doors will open on the left}}\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" rowspan=2 valign=top| '''Eastbound'''\n| <span style=\"color:white\">\u2192</span> {{TMTC bullet|blue|size=5}} '''Blue Line''' towards {{stn|Cleveland Avenue}} <small>([[Yamhill District and Morrison/Southwest 3rd Avenue stations|Yamhill District]])</small> \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"| <span style=\"color:white\">\u2192</span> {{TMTC bullet|red|size=5}} '''Red Line''' towards {{stn|Portland International Airport}} <small>(Yamhill District)</small> \u2192\n|}\n\nThe Pioneer Square stations occupy the sidewalks facing Southwest Yamhill and Morrison streets between Broadway and 6th Avenue in downtown Portland. Pioneer Courthouse Square, commonly known as \"Portland's Living Room\", is situated between the stations' platforms.<ref name=\"community-building-2007\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/pdfs/publications/community_sourcebook.pdf |title=Community Building Sourcebook: Land use and transportation initiatives in Portland, Oregon |date=December 2007 |publisher=TriMet |access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|6\u20136}} Amenities include garbage cans, shelters, and schedule information displays. TriMet's ticket office is located inside the visitor information center on the west side of the square.<ref name=\"community-building-2007\"/>{{rp|6\u20136}} Oregon's first [[Starbucks]] outlet sits adjacent to the western edge of the westbound platform.<ref>{{cite news|title=Starbucks grabs spot in Portland coffee trade|newspaper=The Oregonian|date=August 23, 1989|last=Hamburg|first=Ken}}</ref>\n\nTriMet considers the square a [[transit hub]].<ref name=\"community-building-2007\"/>{{rp|6\u20136}} It is the only location in the MAX system where all five existing light rail services interconnect.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |title=Portland City Center and Transit Mall |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210193921/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The northbound light rail tracks on the Portland Transit Mall run along the immediate east side of the platforms on 6th Avenue; this provides a direct transfer to the MAX platform of [[Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th stations|Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th station]] across the street,<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Pioneer+Courthouse%2FSW+6th+Ave+MAX+Stn/@45.5185392,-122.6779511,18.25z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a0501406169:0xdba87b6b880304d2!8m2!3d45.5189148!4d-122.678597 |title=Pioneer Courthouse/SW 6th Ave MAX Stn |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> which is served by the [[MAX Green Line|Green]] and Yellow lines.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\"/> On the opposite end of this adjacent block, which is occupied by the [[Pioneer Courthouse]],<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Pioneer+Courthouse/@45.5185392,-122.6779511,18.25z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a05062e150d:0x8802daba8b93f854!8m2!3d45.5186849!4d-122.6785527 |title=Pioneer Courthouse |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> is the southbound MAX station, Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Pioneer+Place%2FSW+5th+Ave+MAX+Station/@45.5185392,-122.6779511,18.25z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a050cf4ea0f:0x4cdf598044a8ad23!8m2!3d45.5183125!4d-122.6779392 |title=Pioneer Place/SW 5th Ave MAX Station |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> This station is served by the Green and [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]] lines. The Pioneer Square stations also facilitate transfers to buses serving the Portland Transit Mall.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\"/>\n\n===Service===\n\nThe Pioneer Square stations are served by the MAX Blue Line, which connects the stations to Beaverton and Hillsboro to the west and Gresham to the east, and the MAX Red Line, which connects the stations to Beaverton to the west and Portland International Airport to the east.<ref name=\"MAX system map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/railsystem.pdf |title=Rail System Map with transfers |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210194620/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/railsystem.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8334 |title=Stop ID 8334 \u2013 Pioneer Square South MAX Station |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8383 |title=Stop ID 8383 \u2013 Pioneer Square North MAX Station |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> From the stations, westbound trains take approximately 25{{nbsp}}minutes to reach Beaverton Transit Center and 50{{nbsp}}minutes to reach Hatfield Government Center station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1100_1.pdf |title=MAX Blue Line, Weekday Westbound to Portland City Center and Hillsboro |publisher=TriMet |access-date=May 23, 2019}}</ref> Eastbound trains take approximately 35{{nbsp}}minutes to reach Portland International Airport station and 50{{nbs}}minutes to reach Cleveland Avenue station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1100_0.pdf |title=MAX Blue Line, Weekday Eastbound to Portland City Center and Gresham |publisher=TriMet |access-date=May 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1090_0.pdf |title=MAX Red Line, Weekday To Portland City Center and Airport |publisher=TriMet |access-date=May 23, 2019}}</ref> The stations together recorded an average 5,123 riders on weekdays in fall 2019.<ref name=\"pax-census-fall-2019\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8334 |title=Stop ID 8334 \u2013 Pioneer Square South MAX Station |publisher=TriMet}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8383 |title=Stop ID 8383 \u2013 Pioneer Square North MAX Station |publisher=TriMet}}\n\n{{TriMet railway stations|Blue=y|Red=y}}\n\n[[Category:1986 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:MAX Blue Line]]\n[[Category:MAX Light Rail double stations]]\n[[Category:MAX Red Line]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 1986]]\n[[Category:Southwest Portland, Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{{About-distinguish2|the light rail stations in Portland, Oregon|[[Pioneer Square station]] in Seattle}}\n{{Infobox Station\n | name          = {{MAX infobox header|Pioneer Square South|blue|red}}{{MAX infobox header|Pioneer Square North|blue|red}}\n | type          = [[MAX Light Rail]] stations\n | image         = Pioneer Square South MAX station.jpg\n | image_caption = The platform of Pioneer Square South station in 2009\n | address       = [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]]<br/>[[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]], U.S.\n | country       =\n | line          = {{TMTC bullet|blue|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Blue Line|Blue Line]]{{br}}{{TMTC bullet|red|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Red Line|Red Line]]\n | coordinates   = {{Coord|45|31|08|N|122|40|46|W|format=dms|display=inline,title|type:landmark_region:US-OR}}\n | connections   ={{rint|bus|1}}{{nbsp}}'''[[Portland Transit Mall]]'''{{br}}{{rint|tram|1}}{{nbsp}}'''[[MAX Light Rail]]''':{{Block indent|em=1|1=<nowiki />{{TMTC bullet|green|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Green Line|Green Line]]{{br}}{{TMTC bullet|orange|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}{{TMTC bullet|yellow|size=5}}{{nbsp}}[[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow Line]]{{br}}at [[Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th stations|Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th]]}}\n | platform      = 2 one-way [[side platform]]s\n | tracks        = 1 per split\n | parking       = \n | bicycle       = \n | baggage_check =\n | passengers    = 1,796 (Pioneer Square South){{br}}3,327 (Pioneer Square North){{br}}5,123 (total){{br}}weekday boardings (fall 2019)<ref name=\"pax-census-fall-2019\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/about/pdf/census/2019fall/max_station_passenger_census_report.pdf |title=TriMet MAX Light Rail Passenger Census \u2013 Fall 2019 |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310153349/https://trimet.org/about/pdf/census/2019fall/max_station_passenger_census_report.pdf |archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n | pass_year     =\n | pass_percent  =\n | pass_system   =\n | opened        = {{Start date|1986|09|05}}\n | closed        = \n | rebuilt       = \n | ADA           = yes\n | code          = \n | owned         = [[TriMet]]\n | services      ={{s-rail|title=TMTC}}\n{{s-text|text='''North'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|next=Morrison/SW 3rd|rows2=2|oneway2=yes}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|hide2=yes}}\n{{s-text|text='''South'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Library/SW 9th Ave|next=Yamhill District|rows1=2|oneway1=yes}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|next=Yamhill District|hide1=yes}}\n | other_services_collapsible=yes\n | other_services_header=Former services\n | other_services=\n{{s-rail|title=TMTC}}\n{{s-text|text='''North'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|next=Mall/SW 5th Ave|rows2=3|oneway2=yes|notemid=''1986\u20132020''|note2=(''closed'')}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|hide2=yes|notemid=''2004\u20132009''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Yellow|previous=Galleria/SW 10th Ave|oneway2=yes|notemid=''2004\u20132009''|hide2=yes|type=2009}}\n{{s-text|text='''South'''}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Blue|previous=Library/SW 9th Ave|next=Mall/SW 4th Ave|rows1=3|oneway1=yes|notemid=''1986\u20132020''|note2=(''closed'')}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Red|next=Mall/SW 4th Ave|hide1=yes|notemid=''2001\u20132020''|note2=(''closed'')}}\n{{s-line|system=TMTC|line=Yellow|previous=Library/SW 9th Ave|next=Mall/SW 4th Ave|notemid=''2004\u20132009''|hide1=yes|oneway1=true|note2=(''closed'')}}\n | mpassengers   =\n}}\n'''Pioneer Square South''' and '''Pioneer Square North''' are a pair of [[light rail]] stations in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States, served by [[TriMet]] as part of its [[MAX Light Rail]] system. The platforms occupy the sidewalks of Southwest Yamhill and Morrison streets between Broadway and 6th Avenue in [[downtown Portland]], and are the 21st and 7th stops eastbound on the [[MAX Blue Line|Blue Line]] and the [[MAX Red Line|Red Line]], respectively. They are situated directly west of the [[Portland Transit Mall]] at [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]]; these stations, along with the [[Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th stations]] that are served by the [[MAX Green Line|Green]], [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]], and [[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow]] lines, mark the only [[Interchange station|transfer point]] in the MAX system where riders can board any of the five existing lines.\n\nThe Pioneer Square stations are among the 27 original stations built as part of the Banfield light rail project\u2014Portland's first light rail line. They opened along with the inaugural service of MAX on September 5, 1986. The Red Line began serving the stations in September 2001, initially connecting downtown to [[Portland International Airport]]. In 2003, the Red Line extended westward to [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]]. The Yellow Line also served the stations from 2004 to 2009, connecting downtown to the [[Portland Metropolitan Exposition Center|Expo Center]]; TriMet rerouted this line to serve the transit mall in August 2009.\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Pioneer Courthouse Square}}\n\nThe Portland city block bound by Southwest Morrison and Yamhill streets to the north and south, and 6th Avenue and Broadway to the east and west had previously been occupied by various structures, including a school, a hotel, and a parking garage. In March 1856, a proclamation created School District No. 1, which built the city's first permanent public school at this location.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://oregonhistoryproject.org/articles/historical-records/central-school/#.XnI3dKhKhhE |title=Central School |publisher=[[Oregon Historical Society]] |date=March 17, 2018 |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930101129/https://www.oregonhistoryproject.org/articles/historical-records/central-school/ |archive-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Referred to as Central School, it opened on May 7, 1858.<ref>{{cite news |last=Killen |first=John |title=Throwback Thursday: Portland public schools, started in 1850s, took awhile to catch on |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=June 11, 2015 |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/history/2015/06/throwback_thursday_portland_pu.html |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318151006/https://www.oregonlive.com/history/2015/06/throwback_thursday_portland_pu.html |archive-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> With the arrival of the [[Northern Pacific Railway]] to Portland in 1883, [[Henry Villard]] purchased the site of Central School for $75,000 and began building a first class hotel. The ensuing [[Panic of 1884]] halted construction for five years due to the collapse of Villard's finances. Construction resumed with the help of George B. Markle and other local investors, and the [[Portland Hotel]] opened on April 7, 1890. Over the next several decades, the Portland Hotel would establish itself as the city's social center and the \"place to see and be seen.\"<ref name=\"portland-hotel\">{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=The Portland Hotel: Once the place to see and be seen |date=April 2, 2011 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/O/2011/04/the_portland_hotel_once_the_pl.html |access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pioneer Square MAX station north - Portland, Oregon.JPG|thumb|left|The westbound platform on the north side of the square, 2011]]\n\n[[Meier & Frank]] purchased the Portland Hotel in 1944 and continued operating it until 1951, after which the company tore it down and built a parking garage in its place.<ref name=\"portland-hotel\"/><ref name=\"history-pioneer-photos\">{{cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/multimedia/2013/10/the_history_of_pioneer_courtho.html |last=Vattiat |first=Drew |title=The history of Pioneer Courthouse Square in photos |date=October 4, 2013 |newspaper=The Oregonian |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> In January 1969, Meier & Frank request a permit for the construction of an 11-story, 800-car parking garage, which the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|Portland City Council]] and the Portland Planning Commission rejected following a series of heated public hearings.<ref name=\"began\">{{cite book |last=Halprin |first=Lawrence |last2=Halprin |first2=Anna |title=Where the revolution began |editor=Gragg, Randy |publisher=Spacemaker Press |location=Washington, DC |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-9824392-1-0 |oclc= 449857189}}</ref> The controversial proposal led the local business community and the city to pursue a comprehensive downtown plan that envisioned turning the site into a public space instead.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thesquarepdx.org/history/ |title=History: Timeline |publisher=Pioneer Courthouse Square Administrative Office |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/multimedia/2013/10/history_of_pioneer_courthouse.html |last=Vattiat |first=Drew |title=History of Pioneer Courthouse Square: The winning design and four rejected finalists from 1980 (photos) |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=October 4, 2013 |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> After several negotiations between then-Mayor [[Neil Goldschmidt]] and Meier & Frank, the city purchased the property and in 1980, announced a national design competition for a plaza that would be called [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]].<ref name=\"history-pioneer-photos\"/>\n\nPortland's first light rail line, which planners referred to as the Banfield light rail project, received federal approval for construction in September 1980. Over a year later, TriMet published a conceptual design report of the project for the city that outlined a 27-station, {{convert|15.1|mi|km|1|adj=on}} line, including a pair of light rail stations at Pioneer Courthouse Square. The platforms would be situated along the north and south ends of the square on Southwest Morrison and Yamhill streets.<ref name=\"Conceptual Design\">{{cite report |author=Tri-County Metropolitan Transportation District of Oregon |title=Banfield Light Rail Project: Conceptual Design Information for the City of Portland |url=https://pdxscholar.library.pdx.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1008&context=oscdl_trimet |publisher=TriMet Collection |volume=9 |date=November 1, 1981 |access-date=July 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928184313/http://pdxscholar.library.pdx.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1008&context=oscdl_trimet |archivedate=September 28, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{rp|37\u201338}} Construction of the line commenced in April 1983 in Gresham and largely progressed from east to west,<ref>{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=Tri-Met opens bids on first light-rail track work |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 11, 1983 |page=B1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=Light-rail work gets go-ahead |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 31, 1983 |page=D16}}</ref> with the downtown segment among the final sections to be completed.<ref name=\"light-rails-jolly\">{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=Light rail's jolly trolley progress on track |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 4, 1986 |page=B5}}</ref> Street and sidewalk reconstruction work finally reached downtown in March 1984.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Light-rail work [photo and caption only] |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=March 10, 1984 |quote=Ralph L. Mowatt, a welder for Portland General Electric Co., cuts iron beam in street at Southwest First Avenue and Morrison Street on Friday as construction on the Banfield light-rail project moved downtown this week with utilities beginning to relocate lines. |page=C1}}</ref> While work continued on the line, the city finished building the square and dedicated it on April 6.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ritz |first=Richard E. |title=Flow of people will complete square's design |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 3, 1984 |page=B5}}</ref><ref name=\"soul\">{{cite news |last=Gragg |first=Randy |title=Pioneer Courthouse Square: Soul of the City\" (10th anniversary feature) |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 4, 1994 |pages=A1, A6}}</ref> By March 1986, major light rail construction work had ceased.<ref name=\"light-rails-jolly\"/> Line testing in downtown began with the arrival of the first light rail car the following May.<ref>{{cite news |last=Murphy |first=Bill |title=Downtown debut |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=May 9, 1986 |page=1 |quote=The first Tri-Met light-rail car to appear downtown is towed up Southwest Morrison Street Thursday. It will be open for public inspection at downtown locations for the next week.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Shoppers get first look at Tri-Met light-rail car |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=May 9, 1986 |page=D8}}</ref> \n\nOn September 5, 1986, TriMet officially opened the light rail line, which it named Metropolitan Area Express (MAX), to the public.<ref>{{cite news |last=Federman |first=Stan |title=All aboard! MAX on track; ride free |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=September 5, 1986 |page=1}}</ref> A three-day celebration took place across the route, including at Pioneer Courthouse Square, which hosted an opening ceremony and several concerts.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Riding the Rails; Schedule of events: Sept. 5\u20137 |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=September 5, 1986 |page=T4}}</ref> More than 3,000 people gathered at the square to welcome the 11:45 am arrival of the first train from Gresham.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hayakawa |first=Alan R. |title=Whistle-stop tour inaugurates MAX light rail |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=September 6, 1986 |page=B6}}</ref> Between 1986 and 1998, only one MAX service that ran from [[Cleveland Avenue station|Cleveland Avenue]] in central Gresham to [[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|11th Avenue]] served the Pioneer Square stations. In 1998, TriMet extended this service farther west to [[Hatfield Government Center station|Hatfield Government Center]] in downtown Hillsboro with the opening of the Westside MAX. On September 10, 2001, the Red Line, which connected downtown\u2014and eventually [[Beaverton Transit Center|Beaverton]]\u2014to [[Portland International Airport station|Portland International Airport]] became the second line to serve the station.<ref name=\"oreg-2001-city-that-moves\">{{cite news|last1=Oliver|first1=Gordon|title=Portland now 'the city that moves', mayor says [opening of MAX Red Line]|newspaper=The Oregonian|date=September 11, 2001|page=1}}</ref><ref name=\"direct service Beaverton\">{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |date=August 27, 2003 |title=MAX fares increase, direct service from Beaverton to PDX starts |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D2}}</ref> From 2004 to 2009, the Yellow Line, which ran to the [[Expo Center station|Expo Center]] in North Portland, also stopped at this station until TriMet rerouted it to the new light rail tracks on Portland Transit Mall in August 2009.<ref name=\"tribune2009-0828\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New MAX line opens downtown |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=August 28, 2009 |url=http://pamplinmedia.com/component/content/article?id=54413 |access-date=May 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103091415/http://pamplinmedia.com/component/content/article?id=54413 |archive-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Station details==\n{{stack|float=right|[[File:Pioneer Courthouse Square - west half.jpg|thumb|Entrance to the visitor information center, which also houses TriMet's ticket office]]}}\n{|table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=70 rowspan=3 valign=top|'''Sidewalk{{br}}platform'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100 rowspan=2 valign=top| '''Westbound'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=530| \u2190 {{TMTC bullet|blue|size=5}} '''[[MAX Blue Line|Blue Line]]''' towards {{stn|Hatfield Government Center}} <small>([[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue]])</small>\n|-\n| \u2190 {{TMTC bullet|red|size=5}} '''[[MAX Red Line|Red Line]]''' towards [[Beaverton Transit Center]] <small>(Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue)</small>\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|<small>[[Side platform]], doors will open on the left</small>\n|-\n|colspan=3 align=center| [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]]\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" rowspan=3 valign=top|'''Sidewalk{{br}}platform'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|Side platform, doors will open on the left}}\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" rowspan=2 valign=top| '''Eastbound'''\n| <span style=\"color:white\">\u2192</span> {{TMTC bullet|blue|size=5}} '''Blue Line''' towards {{stn|Cleveland Avenue}} <small>([[Yamhill District and Morrison/Southwest 3rd Avenue stations|Yamhill District]])</small> \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"| <span style=\"color:white\">\u2192</span> {{TMTC bullet|red|size=5}} '''Red Line''' towards {{stn|Portland International Airport}} <small>(Yamhill District)</small> \u2192\n|}\n\nThe Pioneer Square stations occupy the sidewalks facing Southwest Yamhill and Morrison streets between Broadway and 6th Avenue in downtown Portland. Pioneer Courthouse Square, commonly known as \"Portland's Living Room\", is situated between the stations' platforms.<ref name=\"community-building-2007\">{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/pdfs/publications/community_sourcebook.pdf |title=Community Building Sourcebook: Land use and transportation initiatives in Portland, Oregon |date=December 2007 |publisher=TriMet |access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|6\u20136}} Amenities include garbage cans, shelters, and schedule information displays. TriMet's ticket office is located inside the visitor information center on the west side of the square.<ref name=\"community-building-2007\"/>{{rp|6\u20136}} Oregon's first [[Starbucks]] outlet sits adjacent to the western edge of the westbound platform.<ref>{{cite news|title=Starbucks grabs spot in Portland coffee trade|newspaper=The Oregonian|date=August 23, 1989|last=Hamburg|first=Ken}}</ref>\n\nTriMet considers the square a [[transit hub]].<ref name=\"community-building-2007\"/>{{rp|6\u20136}} It is the only location in the MAX system where all five existing light rail services interconnect.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |title=Portland City Center and Transit Mall |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210193921/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The northbound light rail tracks on the Portland Transit Mall run along the immediate east side of the platforms on 6th Avenue; this provides a direct transfer to the MAX platform of [[Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th and Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th stations|Pioneer Courthouse/Southwest 6th station]] across the street,<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Pioneer+Courthouse%2FSW+6th+Ave+MAX+Stn/@45.5185392,-122.6779511,18.25z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a0501406169:0xdba87b6b880304d2!8m2!3d45.5189148!4d-122.678597 |title=Pioneer Courthouse/SW 6th Ave MAX Stn |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> which is served by the [[MAX Green Line|Green]] and Yellow lines.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\"/> On the opposite end of this adjacent block, which is occupied by the [[Pioneer Courthouse]],<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Pioneer+Courthouse/@45.5185392,-122.6779511,18.25z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a05062e150d:0x8802daba8b93f854!8m2!3d45.5186849!4d-122.6785527 |title=Pioneer Courthouse |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> is the southbound MAX station, Pioneer Place/Southwest 5th.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Pioneer+Place%2FSW+5th+Ave+MAX+Station/@45.5185392,-122.6779511,18.25z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a050cf4ea0f:0x4cdf598044a8ad23!8m2!3d45.5183125!4d-122.6779392 |title=Pioneer Place/SW 5th Ave MAX Station |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> This station is served by the Green and [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]] lines. The Pioneer Square stations also facilitate transfers to buses serving the Portland Transit Mall.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\"/>\n\n===Service===\n\nThe Pioneer Square stations are served by the MAX Blue Line, which connects the stations to Beaverton and Hillsboro to the west and Gresham to the east, and the MAX Red Line, which connects the stations to Beaverton to the west and Portland International Airport to the east.<ref name=\"MAX system map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/railsystem.pdf |title=Rail System Map with transfers |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210194620/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/railsystem.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8334 |title=Stop ID 8334 \u2013 Pioneer Square South MAX Station |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8383 |title=Stop ID 8383 \u2013 Pioneer Square North MAX Station |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> From the stations, westbound trains take approximately 25{{nbsp}}minutes to reach Beaverton Transit Center and 50{{nbsp}}minutes to reach Hatfield Government Center station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1100_1.pdf |title=MAX Blue Line, Weekday Westbound to Portland City Center and Hillsboro |publisher=TriMet |access-date=May 23, 2019}}</ref> Eastbound trains take approximately 35{{nbsp}}minutes to reach Portland International Airport station and 50{{nbs}}minutes to reach Cleveland Avenue station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1100_0.pdf |title=MAX Blue Line, Weekday Eastbound to Portland City Center and Gresham |publisher=TriMet |access-date=May 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/schedules/w/t1090_0.pdf |title=MAX Red Line, Weekday To Portland City Center and Airport |publisher=TriMet |access-date=May 23, 2019}}</ref> The stations together recorded an average 5,123 riders on weekdays in fall 2019.<ref name=\"pax-census-fall-2019\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8334 |title=Stop ID 8334 \u2013 Pioneer Square South MAX Station |publisher=TriMet}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/ride/stop.html?stop_id=8383 |title=Stop ID 8383 \u2013 Pioneer Square North MAX Station |publisher=TriMet}}\n\n{{TriMet railway stations|Blue=y|Red=y}}\n\n[[Category:1986 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:MAX Blue Line]]\n[[Category:MAX Light Rail double stations]]\n[[Category:MAX Red Line]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 1986]]\n[[Category:Southwest Portland, Oregon]]\n", "name_user": "Truflip99", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pioneer_Square_South_and_Pioneer_Square_North_stations"}
{"title_page": "Valentinian I", "text_new": "{{short description|Roman emperor}}\n{{Infobox Roman emperor\n| name            = Valentinian I\n| full name       = Flavius Valentinianus\n|regnal name=Imperator Caesar Flavius Valentinianus Augustus\n| succession      =[[Roman Emperor|Emperor of the Roman Empire]]\n| image           = Valentiniano Primo.jpg\n| caption         = Valentinian I\n| reign           = 26 February{{snd}}28 March 364 (whole empire);<br>26 March 364{{snd}}17 November 375 (emperor of the [[Western Roman Empire|west]])\n| predecessor     = [[Jovian (Emperor)|Jovian]]\n| successor       = [[Valens]], [[Gratian]] and [[Valentinian II]]\n| spouse 1        = [[Marina Severa]]\n| spouse 2        = [[Justina (empress)|Justina]]\n| issue           = [[Gratian]] <br>[[Valentinian II]]<br> [[Galla (wife of Theodosius I)|Galla]]<br> Grata <br> Justa\n| dynasty         = [[Valentinian dynasty|Valentinian]]\n| father          = [[Gratian the Elder]]\n| mother          = \n| religion        = [[Nicene Christianity]]\n| birth_date   = {{date of birth|321|7|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Cibalae]], [[Pannonia Secunda]] ([[Vinkovci]], present-day [[Croatia]])\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|375|11|17|321|7|3|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Brigetio]], [[Pannonia Valeria]] ([[Sz\u0151ny]], present-day [[Hungary]])\n| place of burial = \n| reg-type={{nowrap|Co-emperor}}|regent=[[Valens]] {{small|([[List of Byzantine Emperors|Eastern Emperor]])}}|title=[[Augustus (honorific)|Augustus]] of the [[Western Roman Empire]]}}\n\n'''Valentinian I''' ({{lang-la|Flavius Valentinianus Augustus}};<ref>In [[Classical Latin]], Valentinian's name would read as FLAVIVS VALENTINIANVS AVGVSTVS.</ref> {{lang-grc-gre|\u039f\u1f50\u03b1\u03bb\u03b5\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03b9\u03b1\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2}}; 3 July 321{{snd}}17 November 375), also known as '''Valentinian the Great''',<ref>Philip Schaff, ''A Select Library of the Nicene and post Nicene Fathers of the Christian Church, Volume 3''. Eerdmans Publishing, University of California, 1956. p 146</ref><ref>Edward Kenneth Rand, ''Founders of the Middle Ages''. Dover Publications, University of Michigan, 1957. p 76</ref><ref>Michael Whitby, Mary Whitby, ''Chronicon Paschale 284\u2013628 AD''. Liverpool University Press, University of Michigan, 1989. p 51, 53</ref><ref>Gilbert Dagron, ''Emperor and priest: the imperial office in Byzantium''. Cambridge University Press, 2003. p 26</ref> was [[Roman emperor]] from 364 to 375. Upon becoming emperor he made his brother [[Valens]] his co-emperor, giving him rule of the [[Eastern Roman Empire|eastern provinces]] while Valentinian retained the [[Western Roman Empire|west]].\n\nDuring his reign, Valentinian fought successfully against the [[Alamanni]], [[Quadi]], and [[Sarmatians]]. Most notable was his victory over the Alamanni in 367 at the [[Battle of Solicinium]]. His brilliant general [[Count Theodosius]] defeated a revolt in [[Africa (Roman province)|Africa]] and the [[Great Conspiracy]], a coordinated assault on [[Roman Britain]] by [[Picts]], [[Scottish people|Scots]], and [[Saxons]]. Valentinian was also the last emperor to conduct campaigns across both the [[Rhine]] and [[Danube]] rivers. Valentinian rebuilt and improved the fortifications along the frontiers, even building fortresses in enemy territory.\n\nDue to the successful nature of his reign and the rapid decline of the empire after his death, he is often considered to be the \"last great western emperor\". He founded the [[Valentinian Dynasty]], with his sons [[Gratian]] and [[Valentinian II]] succeeding him in the western half of the empire.\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Solidus de Valentinien MAN.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Solidus of emperor Valentinian I.]]\nValentinian was born in 321<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXX.6.6</ref> at [[Cibalae]] in southern [[Pannonia]] (now [[Vinkovci]] in [[Croatia]]) into an [[Illyro-Romans|Illyro-Roman]] family.<ref name=\"Lenski2002\">{{cite book|last=Lenski|first=Noel Emmanuel|title=Failure of empire: Valens and the Roman state in the fourth century A.D.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uvXo39xOV8kC&pg=PA56|accessdate=12 October 2010|year=2002|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-23332-4|page=56}}</ref> Valentinian and his younger brother [[Valens]] were the sons of [[Gratian the Elder|Gratianus Major]], a prominent commander during the reigns of emperors [[Constantine the Great|Constantine I]] and [[Constans I]].<ref name=tomlinp2>{{cite book |author=Tomlin, R. |title=The Emperor Valentinian I |year=1973 |page=2}}</ref> He and his brother grew up on the family estate where they were educated in a variety of subjects, including painting and sculpting.<ref>Aurelius Victor, ''Epitome de Caesaribus''. 45.5</ref>\n\nGratian the Elder was promoted to ''[[Comes]] Africae'' in the late 320s or early 330s, and the young Valentinian accompanied his father to Africa.<ref name=tomlinp4>{{cite book |author=Tomlin, R. |title=The Emperor Valentinian I |year=1973 |page=4}}</ref> However, Gratian was soon accused of embezzlement and was forced to retire.<ref name=tomlinp4 /> Valentinian joined the army in the late 330s and later probably acquired the position of ''[[Domesticus (Roman Empire)|protector domesticus]]''.<ref name=tomlinp4 /> Gratian was later recalled during the early 340s and was made ''comes'' of [[Roman Britain|Britannia]].<ref name=tomlinp4 /> After holding this post, Gratianus retired to the family estate in Cibalae.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXX.7.3</ref>\n\nIn 350, Constans I was assassinated by agents of the [[usurper]] [[Magnentius]], a commander in [[Gaul]] proclaimed emperor by his soldiers.{{cn|date=August 2018}} [[Constantius II]], older brother of Constans and emperor in the East, promptly set forth towards Magnentius with a large army.<ref name=\"Zosimus, New History II.60\">Zosimus, ''New History'' II.60</ref> The following year the two emperors met in Pannonia. The ensuing [[Battle of Mursa Major]] resulted in a costly victory for Constantius.<ref>[[Joannes Zonaras|Zonaras]], ''Extracts of History'' XIII.8.5\u201313</ref> Two years later he defeated Magnentius again in southern Gaul at the [[Battle of Mons Seleucus]].<ref>[[Eutropius (historian)|Eutropius]], ''Historiae Romanae Breviarium'' X.11-2</ref> Magnentius, now realizing the futility of continuing his revolt, committed suicide in August that year; making Constantius sole ruler of the empire.<ref>[[Eutropius (historian)|Eutropius]], ''Historiae Romanae Breviarium'' X.12</ref> It was around this time that Constantius confiscated Gratianus' property, for supposedly showing hospitality to Magnentius when he was in Pannonia.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> Despite his father's fall from favor, Valentinian does not seem to have been adversely affected at this time, making it unlikely he ever fought for the usurper.<ref name=tomlinp13 /> It is known that Valentinian was in the region during the conflict, but what involvement he had in the war, if any, is unknown.<ref name=tomlinp13>{{cite book |author=Tomlin, R. |title=The Emperor Valentinian I |year=1973 |page=13}}</ref>\n\n==Service under Constantius and Julian==\nThe conflict between Magnentius and Constantius had allowed the [[Alamanni]] and [[Franks]] to take advantage of the confusion and cross the [[Rhine]], attacking several important settlements and fortifications.<ref name=\"tomlinp4\"/><ref name=tomlinp13 /> In 355, after deposing his cousin Gallus but still feeling the crises of the empire too much for one emperor to handle, Constantius raised his cousin [[Julian the Apostate|Julian]] to the rank of ''Caesar''.<ref name=tomlinp4 /> With the situation in Gaul rapidly deteriorating, Julian was made at least nominal commander of one of the two main armies in Gaul, [[Barbatio]] being commander of the other.<ref name=tomlinp4 /> Constantius devised a strategy where Julian and Barbatio would operate in a pincer movement against the Alamanni.<ref name=tomlinp13 /> However, a band of Alamanni slipped past Julian and Barbatio and attacked [[Lugdunum]] ([[Lyon]]). Julian sent the tribunes Valentinian and [[Bainobaudes]] to watch the road the raiders would have to return by. However, their efforts were hindered by Barbatio and his tribune [[Cella (soldier)|Cella]]. The Alamanni king [[Chnodomarius]] took advantage of the situation and attacked the Romans in detail, inflicting heavy losses.<ref name=tomlinp13 /> Barbatio complained to Constantius and the debacle was blamed on Valentinian and Bainobaudes, who were cashiered from the army.<ref name=tomlinp13 />\n\nWith his career in ruins, Valentinian returned to his new family estate in [[Sirmium]]. Two years later his first son [[Gratian]] was born by his wife [[Marina Severa]].<ref name=tomlinp14>{{cite book |author=Tomlin, R. |title=The Emperor Valentinian I |year=1973 |page=14}}</ref> Valentinian's actions and location become uncertain around this time, but he was likely exiled.<ref>Sources give different commands Valentinian held at the time and vastly different places of exile: [[Philostorgius]] says Constantius exiled Valentinian to [[Thebes, Egypt|Thebes]] in [[Roman Egypt|Egypt]], [[Sosomen]] to [[Melitene]] in [[Lesser Armenia|Armenia]], the [[Paschal Chronicle]] to [[Selymbria]] in [[Thrace]], and [[Theodoret]] to \"a distant fort\". Tomlin, p. 14.</ref> Theodoret say that this was because he'd reacted angrily when a pagan temple attendant sprinkled water on him, saying \"I am not purified, but defiled\", and striking the priest.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gaddis |first1=Michael |title=There Is No Crime for Those Who Have Christ: Religious Violence in the Christian Roman Empire |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0520286245 |page=256 |url=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=iaowDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA256&lpg=PA256&dq=Valentinian+exiled+defile&source=bl&ots=okX_hhqUVR&sig=ACfU3U0FWUFQcdFE2Mb7FIjNyWN0yYmhPQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjG0tLU-ZPgAhUWVH0KHXpUAtQQ6AEwAHoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=Valentinian%20exiled%20defile&f=false |accessdate=29 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Rise to power==\nAt the news of Julian's death on a campaign against the Sassanids, the army hastily declared a commander, [[Jovian (Emperor)|Jovian]], emperor. The army still found itself beleaguered by Persian attacks, forcing Jovian to accept humiliating peace terms.<ref name=tomlinp16>{{cite book |author=Tomlin, R. |title=The Emperor Valentinian I |year=1973 |page=16}}</ref> Jovian's authority within the empire was still insecure, so he sent a notary [[Procopius (notary)|Procopius]] and the tribune [[Memoridus]] west to announce his accession.<ref name=tomlinp16 /> During Jovian's reign Valentinian was promoted to tribune of a ''Scutarii'' (elite infantry) regiment, and was dispatched to Ancyra. Jovian's rule would be short \u2013 only eight months \u2013 and before he could even consolidate his position in [[Constantinople]] he died en route between [[Ancyra]] and [[Nicaea]]. His death was attributed to either assassination by poisoning or accidental carbon monoxide poisoning. Jovian is remembered mostly for restoring Christianity to its previous favored status under Constantine and his sons.\n\nThe army marched to Nicaea, and a meeting of civil and military officials was convened to choose a new emperor. The purple was offered to [[Sallustius]], who had refused it once before on Julian's death. The prefect declined, and did so again on behalf of his son when the offer was extended to him.<ref>[[Edward Gibbon]], ''The Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire'', (The Modern Library, 1932), ch. XXV., pp. 845, 846</ref> Two different names were proposed: [[Aequitius]], a tribune of the first Scutarii, and Januarius, a relative of Jovian's in charge of military supplies in Illyricum. Both were rejected; Aequitius as too rough and boorish,<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVI.1.4</ref> Januarius because he was too far away.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVI.1.5</ref> As a man well qualified and at hand, the assembly finally agreed upon Valentinian,  and sent messengers to inform him in Ancyra.\n\n==Emperor==\n{{Refimprove section|date=February 2017}}\nValentinian accepted the acclamation on 26 February 364. As he prepared to make his accession speech the soldiers threatened to riot, apparently uncertain as to where his loyalties lay. Valentinian reassured them that the army was his greatest priority. According to [[Ammianus]] the soldiers were astounded by Valentinian\u2019s bold demeanor and his willingness to assume the imperial authority. To further prevent a succession crisis he agreed to pick a co-Augustus. His decision to elect a fellow-emperor could also be construed as a move to appease any opposition among the civilian officials in the eastern portion of the Empire. By agreeing to appoint a co-ruler, he assured the eastern officials that someone with imperial authority would remain in the east to protect their interests.\n\nValentinian selected his brother Valens as co-Augustus at Constantinople on 28 March 364. This was done over the objections of [[Dagalaifus (Roman Consul, 366)|Dagalaifus]], the ''[[magister equitum]]''. Ammianus makes it clear that Valens was subordinate to his brother. The remainder of 364 was spent delegating administrative duties and military commands. According to the 5th century historian [[Zosimus]], who as a [[Pagan]] was inclined to revile the restorer of [[Christianity]], all the ministers and officials appointed by Julian were summarily dismissed in disgrace; modern authorities have qualified the assertion.<ref>Gibbon, p. 849 note</ref> It is certain that some reshuffling of commands occurred along with the division of the provinces, but the changes were strictly based on merit. The [[Sophists]] and philosophers who had proliferated in the court of the apostate, drawing large salaries for delusive services, were cashiered.<ref>Gibbon, ch. XXIII., pp. 771-73; ch. XXV., p. 849</ref>  Valentinian retained the services of Dagalaifus and promoted Aequitius to ''Comes Illyricum''. Valens was given the [[Prefecture of Oriens]], governed by [[prefect]] [[Salutius]]. Valentinian gained control of [[Praetorian prefecture of Italy|Italy]], [[Prefecture of Gaul|Gaul]], [[Praetorian prefecture of Africa|Africa]], and [[Prefecture of Illyricum|Illyricum]]. Valens resided in [[Constantinople]], while Valentinian\u2019s court was at [[Mediolanum]].\n\n===Campaigns in Gaul and Germania===\n[[File:Colosso-de-barletta.jpg|thumb|upright|The emperor depicted in the [[Colossus of Barletta]] could very well be Valentinian I.<ref>Cunliffe B. W. (1994) ''Rome and Her Empire'', Constable, p. 317</ref>]]\n\nIn 365 the [[Alamanni]] crossed the Rhine and invaded Gaul. Simultaneously, [[Procopius (usurper)|Procopius]] \u2013 the last scion of the [[Constantinian dynasty]] \u2013 began his revolt against Valens in the east. According to Ammianus, Valentinian received news of both the Alamanni and Procopius' revolt on 1 November while on his way to [[Paris]]. He initially sent Dagalaifus to fight the Alamanni<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVI.5.9</ref> while he himself made preparations to march east and help Valens. After receiving counsel from his court and deputations from the leading Gallic cities begging him to stay and protect Gaul, he decided to remain in Gaul and fight the Alamanni.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVI.5.12</ref><ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVI.5.13</ref>\nValentinian advanced to [[Durocortorum]] and sent two generals, Charietto and Severianus, against the invaders.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVII.1.2</ref> Both generals were promptly defeated and killed.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVII.1.4</ref> In 366, Dagalaifus was sent against the Alamanni but he was also ineffective.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVII.2.1</ref> Late in the campaigning season Dagalaifus was replaced by Jovinus, a general from the court of Valentinian. After several victories along the [[Meuse river]] Jovinus pushed the Alamanni out of Gaul and was awarded the consulate the following year for his efforts.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVII.2.10</ref>\n\nIn early 367 Valentinian was distracted from launching a punitive expedition against the Alamanni due to crises in Britain and northern Gaul. The Alamanni promptly re-crossed the Rhine and plundered [[Moguntiacum]]. Valentinian succeeded in arranging the assassination of [[Vithicabius]], an Alamannic leader, but Valentinian was more determined to bring the Alamanni under Roman hegemony. Valentinian spent the entire winter of 367 gathering a massive army for a spring offensive. He summoned the ''Comes Italiae'' Sebastianus, with the Italian and Illyrian legions, to join Jovinus and Severus, the ''[[magister peditum]]''. In the spring of 368 Valentinian, his eight-year-old son Gratian and the army crossed the Rhine and [[Main (river)|Main]] rivers into Alamannic territory. They did not encounter any resistance initially \u2013 burning any dwellings or food stores they found along the way. Finally, Valentinian fought the Alamanni in the [[Battle of Solicinium]]; the Romans were victorious<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVII.10.15</ref> but suffered heavy casualties.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVII.10.16</ref> A temporary peace was reached and Valentinian returned to [[Trier]] for the winter.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVII.10.17</ref> During 369, Valentinian ordered new defensive works to be constructed and old structures refurbished along the length of the Rhine\u2019s west bank.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVIII.2.1</ref> Boldly, he ordered the construction of a fortress across the Rhine in the mountains near modern [[Heidelberg]].<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVIII.2.2</ref> The Alamanni sent envoys to protest, but they were dismissed. The Alamanni attacked the fortress while it was still under construction and destroyed it.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVIII.2.8</ref>\n\nIn 370 the [[Saxons]] renewed their attacks on northern Gaul. Nannienus, the ''comes'' in charge of the troops in northern Gaul, urged Severus to come to his aid. After several modest successes, a truce was called and the Saxons handed over to the Romans young men fit for duty in the Roman military \u2013 in exchange for free passage back to their homeland. The Romans ambushed them and destroyed the entire invading force.<ref>Rike, R.L., ''Apex Omnium: Religion in the Res Gestae of Ammianus'' (1987), pg. 91; Jones, Martindale and Morris, ''The Prosopography of the Later Roman Empire'' Vol. I (1971), pgs. 615-616</ref>\n\nValentinian meanwhile tried to persuade the [[Burgundians]] \u2013 bitter enemies of the Alamanni \u2013 to attack [[Macrian]], a powerful Alamannic chieftain. If the Alamanni tried to flee, Valentinian would be waiting for them with his army. Negotiations with the Burgundians broke down when Valentinian, in his usual high-handed manner, refused to meet with the Burgundian envoys and personally assure them of Roman support. Nevertheless, rumors of a Roman alliance with the Burgundians did have the effect of scattering the Alamanni through fear of an imminent attack from their enemies. This event allowed the ''[[magister equitum]]'' [[Count Theodosius|Theodosius]] to attack the Alamanni through Raetia \u2013 taking many Alamannic prisoners. These captured Alamanni were settled in the [[Po river]] valley in Italy, where they were still settled at the time Ammianus wrote his history.\n\nValentinian campaigned unsuccessfully for four more years to defeat Macrian who in 372 barely escaped capture by Theodosius. Meanwhile, Valentinian continued to recruit heavily from Alamanni friendly to Rome. He sent the Alamannic king Fraomarius, as a Tribune, to Britain in 372-373 with an army in order to replenish troops there and made the noblemen Bitheridius and [[Hortarius]] commanders in his army although Hortarius was soon executed for conspiring with Macrian. Valentinian\u2019s Alamannic campaigns, however, were hampered by troubles first in Africa, and later on the Danube river. In 374 Valentinian was forced to make peace with Macrian because the Emperor's presence was needed to counter an invasion of Illyricum by the Quadi and Sarmatians.\n\n===The Great Conspiracy===\nIn 367, Valentinian received reports from Britain that a combined force of [[Picts]], [[Attacotti]] and [[Scoti|Scots]] had killed the ''[[Comes litoris Saxonici]]'' [[Nectaridus]] and ''[[Dux Britanniarum]]'' [[Fullofaudes]]. At the same time, Frankish and Saxon forces were raiding the coastal areas of northern Gaul. The empire was in the midst of the [[Great Conspiracy]] \u2013 and was in danger of losing control of Britain altogether. Valentinian set out for Britain, sending ''Comes domesticorum'' Severus ahead of him to investigate. Severus was not able to correct the situation and returned to Gaul, meeting Valentinian at [[Samarobriva]]. Valentinian then sent Jovinus to Britain and promoted Severus to magister peditum. It was at this time that Valentinian fell ill and a battle for succession broke out between Severus, a representative of the army, and Rusticus Julianus, ''magister memoriae'' and a representative of the Gallic nobility. Valentinian soon recovered however and appointed his son Gratian as his co-Augustus in the west. Ammianus remarks that such an action was unprecedented. Jovinus quickly returned saying that he needed more men to take care of the situation. In 368 Valentinian appointed Theodosius as the new ''[[Comes Britanniarum]]'' with instructions to return Britain to Roman rule. Meanwhile, Severus and Jovinus were to accompany the emperor on his campaign against the Alamanni.\n\nTheodosius arrived in 368 with the [[Batavi (Germanic tribe)|Batavi]], [[Heruli]], Jovii and Victores legions. Landing at [[Rutupi\u00e6]], he proceeded to [[Londinium]] restoring order to southern Britain. Later, he rallied the remaining garrison which was originally stationed in Britain; it was apparent the units had lost their cohesiveness when Fullofaudes and Nectaridus had been defeated. Theodosius sent for [[Civilis (vicarius)|Civilis]] to be installed as the new [[vicarius]] of the [[diocese]] and [[Dulcitius]] as an additional general.\nIn 369, Theodosius set about reconquering the areas north of [[London]]; putting down the revolt of [[Valentinus (rebel)|Valentinus]], the brother-in-law of a [[vicarius]], [[Maximinus (praetorian prefect)|Maximinus]]. Subsequently, Theodosius restored the rest of Britain to the empire and rebuilt many fortifications \u2013 renaming northern Britain '[[Valentia (Roman Britain)|Valentia]]'. After his return in 369, Valentinian promoted Theodosius to ''magister equitum'' in place of Jovinus.\n\n===Revolt in Africa and crises on the Danube===\n[[File:Missorio di valentiniano I, argento, 364-75 ca., dall'arve, 02.JPG|thumb|right|Silver missorium (heavily worn) believed to depict Valentinian I. The armoured and haloed emperor is flanked by infantry soldiers, he holds a [[labarum]] in one hand and an orb surmounted by a figure of Victory in the other, ca. 364-375]]\nIn 372, the rebellion of [[Firmus (4th century usurper)|Firmus]] broke out in the still-devastated African provinces. This rebellion was driven by the corruption of the ''comes'' Romanus. Romanus took sides in the murderous disputes among the legitimate and illegitimate children of Nubel, a Moorish prince and leading Roman client in Africa. Resentment of Romanus' peculations and his failure to defend the province from desert nomads caused some of the provincials to revolt. Valentinian                   sent in Theodosius to restore imperial control. Over the following two years Theodosius uncovered Romanus' crimes, arrested him and his supporters, and defeated Firmus.\n\nIn 373, hostilities erupted with the [[Quadi]], a group of Germanic-speaking people living on the upper Danube. Like the Alamanni, the Quadi were outraged that Valentinian was building fortifications in their territory. They complained and sent deputations to the ''magister armorum per Illyricum'' Aequitius, who promised to refer the matter to Valentinian. However, the increasingly influential minister Maximinus, now praetorian prefect of Gaul, blamed Aequitius to Valentinian for the trouble, and managed to have him promote his son Marcellianus to finish the project.<ref>Gibbon, p. 894</ref> The protests of Quadic leaders continued to delay the project, and to put an end to their clamor Marcellianus murdered the Quadic king [[Gabinius (king)|Gabinius]] at a banquet ostensibly arranged for peaceful negotiations. This roused the Quadi to war, along with their allies the Sarmatians. During the fall, they crossed the Danube and began ravaging the province of [[Pannonia Valeria]]. The marauders could not penetrate the fortified cities, but they heavily damaged the unprotected countryside. Two legions were sent in but failed to coordinate and were routed by the Sarmatians. Meanwhile, another group of Sarmatians invaded [[Moesia]], but were driven back by the son of Theodosius, ''Dux Moesiae'' and later emperor [[Theodosius I|Theodosius]].\n\nValentinian did not receive news of these crises until late 374. The following spring he set out from Trier and arrived at [[Carnuntum]], which was deserted. There he was met by Sarmatian envoys who begged forgiveness for their actions. Valentinian replied that he would investigate what had happened and act accordingly. Valentinian ignored Marcellianus\u2019 treacherous actions and decided to punish the Quadi. He was accompanied by Sebastianus and [[Merobaudes (general)|Merobaudes]], and spent the summer months preparing for the campaign. In the fall he crossed the Danube at [[Aquincum]] into Quadi territory.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXX.5.13</ref> After pillaging Quadi lands without opposition, he retired to [[Sabaria|Savaria]] to winter quarters.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXX.5.14</ref>\n\n====Death====\nWithout waiting for the spring he decided to continue campaigning and moved from Savaria to [[Szony|Brigetio]]. Once he arrived on 17 November, he received a deputation from the Quadi. In return for supplying fresh recruits to the Roman army, the Quadi were to be allowed to leave in peace. However, before the envoys left they were granted an audience with Valentinian. The envoys insisted that the conflict was caused by the building of Roman forts in their lands; furthermore individual bands of Quadi were not necessarily bound to the rule of the chiefs who had made treaties with the Romans \u2013 and thus might attack the Romans at any time. The attitude of the envoys so enraged Valentinian that he suffered a burst blood vessel in the skull while angrily yelling at them, provoking his death<ref>{{cite book|last=Gibbon|first=Edward|title=The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire: Edited in Seven Volumes with Introduction, Notes, Appendices, and Index|date=2012|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781108050739|page=66|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zgtcg0nMg_IC&pg=PA66}}</ref> on November 17, 375.\n\n== Reputation ==\n[[A.H.M. Jones]] writes that although Valentinian I was \"less of a boor\" than his chief rival for election to the imperial throne, \"he was of a violent and brutal temper, and not only uncultivated himself, but hostile to cultivated persons\". According to [[Ammianus Marcellinus|Ammianus]], \"he hated the well-dressed and educated and wealthy and well-born\". He was, however, an able soldier and a conscientious administrator, and took an interest in the welfare of the humbler classes, from which his father had risen. Unfortunately his good intentions were often frustrated by a bad choice of ministers, and \"an obstinate belief in their merits despite all evidence to the contrary.\"<ref>A.H.M. Jones, ''The Later Roman Empire, 284\u2013602: A Social, Economic and Administrative Survey'' (Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University, 1986), p. 139.</ref> He was a founder of schools, and provided medical attendance for the poor of [[Rome]], by appointing a physician for each of the fourteen districts of the city.<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Valentinian I.|volume=27|page=851}}</ref> He also reissued an edict of [[Constantine I]] making infanticide a capital offence.<ref>Gibbon, ch. XIV., p. 375; ch. XXV., p. 859</ref>\n\nNotwithstanding the benevolence of these more generous edicts, Valentinian was remarkable for cruelty and barbarism in his private affairs.\nHe often had servants and attendants executed on trifling charges, and was reportedly accustomed to keep two bears, known as ''Micca Aurea'' (''golden camel''), and ''Innocence'', in an iron cage which was transported wherever he went, whom he employed to execute the sentence, which he often delivered, of capital punishment. At length ''Innocence'', when she was considered to have faithfully discharged her office, was released with the emperor's good wishes into her native wilds.<ref>[[Charles Kingsley]], ''The Roman And The Teuton, A Series Of Lectures delivered before the University of Cambridge'', (Macmillan And Co., 1889, London), lecture II, ''The Dying Empire''</ref>\n\nValentinian was a [[Christians|Christian]] but permitted liberal religious freedom to all his subjects, proscribing only some forms of rituals such as particular types of sacrifices, and banning the practice of magic. Again, Valentinian steadily set his face against the increasing wealth and worldliness of the clergy. He issued a pointed edict via [[Pope Damasus I]], forbidding the grant of bequests to Christian clergy-men; and another forcing members of the sacerdotal order to discharge the public duties owed on account of their property, or else relinquish it.<ref>Gibbon, ch. XXV., p. 864; ch. XX., p. 662, editor's note</ref><ref name=\"EB1911\"/>\n\n[[Socrates of Constantinople|Socrates Scholasticus]] gives an interesting account in his Historia Ecclesiastica of Valentinian's marriages, that has inspired some to call this emperor [[Polygamy in Christianity|polygamous]]. According to the text: the empress [[Justina (empress)|Justina]] \"became known to [[Marina Severa]], wife of the emperor Valentinian, and had frequent dialogue with the empress, until their intimacy at length grew to such an extent that they were accustomed to bathe together. When Severa saw Justina in the bath she was greatly struck with the beauty of the virgin, and spoke of her to the emperor; saying that the daughter of Justus was so lovely a creature, and possessed of such symmetry of form, that she herself, though a woman, was altogether charmed with her. The emperor, treasuring this description by his wife in his own mind, considered with himself how he could espouse Justina, without repudiating Severa, as she had borne him Gratian, whom he had created Augustus a little while before. He accordingly framed a law, and caused it to be published throughout all the cities, by which any man was permitted to have two lawful wives. The law was promulgated and he married Justina, by whom he had Valentinian the younger.\" (Book IV, chapt. 31.)<ref>Translated by A.C. Zenos. From Nicene and Post-Nicene Fathers, Second Series, Vol. 2. Edited by Philip Schaff and Henry Wace. (Buffalo, NY: Christian Literature Publishing Co., 1890.)</ref>\n\nThis story is only known from Socrates and no trace of any edict by any emperor allowing polygamy exists. Valentinian I may have divorced Severa according to Roman Law, which allowed for divorce (see [[Women in Ancient Rome]]).<ref>Frier, Bruce W. and McGinn, Thomas A.J.: A Casebook on Roman Family Law (American Philological Association) OUP USA 2003. Part D, The End of Marriage</ref> However, since divorce was not acknowledged by Christians,<ref>Matthew 19, 4\u20136.</ref> Socrates contemptuously describes him as a bigamist. It is also possible that Socrates attempted to accuse Justina, who was an [[Arianism|Arian]], of fornication, a common aspersion against other cults. According to [[John Malalas]], the [[Chronicon Paschale]], and [[John of Nikiu]], the empress Severa was banished by Valentinian I for conducting an illegal transaction, before he consorted with Justina. Barnes believes this story to be an attempt to justify the divorce of Valentinian I without accusing the emperor.<ref>Timothy Barnes, \"Ammianus Marcellinus and the Representation of Historical Reality\" (1998), p. 123\u2013125</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Byzantine Empire}}\n*[[List of Byzantine emperors]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n===Primary sources===\n*Ammianus Marcellinus. Rerum gestarum libri qui supersunt. W. Seyfarth, ed. 3 vols. Leipzig, 1978.\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Charles|first=Robert H.|authorlink=Robert Charles (scholar)|title=The Chronicle of John, Bishop of Nikiu: Translated from Zotenberg's Ethiopic Text|year=2007|origyear=1916|location=Merchantville, NJ|publisher=Evolution Publishing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KgZ-DOr77OQC}}\n*Consularia Constantinopolitana. T. Mommsen ed., Monumenta Germaniae Historica, Auctores Antiquissimi. Volume 9. Berlin, 1892.\n*Codex Theodosianus. T. Mommsen, P.M. Meyer, and P. Kr\u00fcger, eds. Theodosiani libri XVI cum constitutionibus Sirmondianis et leges novellae ad Theodosianum pertinentes (2 vols.). Berlin, 1905.\n*Corpus Inscriptionum Latinarum. Vol. 6. T. Mommsen, ed. Berlin, 1875.\n*Epitome de Caesaribus. F.R. Pichlmayr, ed. Leipzig, 1961.\n*Jerome. Chronicon. R. Helm, ed., in Malcolm Drew Donalson, A Translation of Jerome\u2019s Chronicon with Historical Commentary. Lewiston, NY, 1996.\n*Orosius. Adversus paganos historiarum libri septem. Z. Zangemeister, ed. Corpus scriptorum ecclesiasticorum latinorum 5. Vienna, 1882.\n*Socrates. Historia Ecclesiastica. J.P. Migne ed., Patrologia Graeca 67. Paris, 1864.\n*Sozomen. Historia Ecclesiastica. J.P. Migne ed., Patrologia Graeca 67. Paris, 1864.\n*Theoderet. Historia Ecclesiastica. J.P. Migne ed., Patrologia Graeca 82. Paris, 1864.\n*Zosimus. Historia nova. Fran\u00e7ois Paschoud, ed. and trans., Zosime: Histoire Nouvelle (3 vols.). Paris, 1971\u201389.\n*Ammian, Books&nbsp;26\u201130 [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/home.html#26 Uchicago.edu]. English summaries. Main text in Latin.\n\n===Secondary accounts===\n* [http://www.roman-emperors.org/vali.htm ''De Imperatoribus Romanis''] English text.\n* [[Edward Gibbon]], ''The Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire'', 1776.\n* M. Grant, ''The Roman Emperors'', 1985.\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle = Valentinian I.|volume=27 |page=851}} <!-- Unusually, we cite EB1911 in two ways, because its body contains an alternative summary of the biography, and also some specific attributions (see the references secction) -->\n* {{in lang|de}} Schmidt-Hofner, Sebastian. ''Reagieren und Gestalten: der Regierungsstil des spaetroemischen Kaisers am Beispiel der Gesetzgebung Valentinians I''. Muenchen: Beck, 2008. 398 p. (Vestigia, Bd. 58).\n* [[Ernst Stein]], ''Histoire du Bas-Empire,'' vol. i, chap. 4 (1959).\n* {{cite CE1913|wstitle = Valentinian|volume=16}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons}}\n* This [http://www.fourthcentury.com/index.php/imperial-laws-chart-364 list of Roman laws of the fourth century] shows laws passed by Valentinian I relating to Christianity.\n\t\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Valentinian dynasty]]||321|17 November|375}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Jovian (Emperor)|Jovian]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[List of Roman Emperors|Roman Emperor]]\n        | years=364\u2013375\n        | alongside=[[Valens]] }}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Valens]], [[Gratian]] and [[Valentinian II]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef | before= [[Jovian (Emperor)|Jovian]],<br />[[Varronianus (son of Jovian)|Varronianus]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[List of Roman Consuls|Consul]] of the [[Roman Empire]] | years=365 |regent1= [[Valens]]}}\n{{s-aft | after= [[Gratian]],<br />Dagalaifus}}\n{{s-bef | before= [[Flavius Lupicinus (consul 367)|Flavius Lupicinus]],<br />Flavius Iovinus}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[List of Roman Consuls|Consul]] of the [[Roman Empire]] | years=368 |regent1= [[Valens]]}}\n{{s-aft | after= [[Valentinianus Galates]],<br />[[Victor (consul 369)|Flavius Victor]]}}\n{{s-bef | before= [[Valentinianus Galates]],<br />[[Victor (consul 369)|Flavius Victor]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[List of Roman Consuls|Consul]] of the [[Roman Empire]] | years=370 |regent1= [[Valens]]}}\n{{s-aft | after= [[Gratian]],<br />[[Sextus Claudius Petronius Probus]]}}\n{{s-bef | before= [[Domitius Modestus]],<br />[[Flavius Arinthaeus]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[List of Roman Consuls|Consul]] of the [[Roman Empire]] | years=373 |regent1= [[Valens]]}}\n{{s-aft | after= [[Gratian]],<br />Flavius Equitius}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Roman Emperors}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Valentinian 01}}\n[[Category:321 births]]\n[[Category:375 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Vinkovci]]\n[[Category:4th-century Christians]]\n[[Category:4th-century Roman emperors]]\n[[Category:4th-century Byzantine emperors]]\n[[Category:Imperial Roman consuls]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Church of the Holy Apostles]]\n[[Category:Valentinian dynasty]]\n[[Category:Flavii]]\n[[Category:Illyrian people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Roman emperor}}\n{{Infobox Roman emperor\n| name            = Valentinian I\n| full name       = Flavius Valentinianus\n|regnal name=Imperator Caesar Flavius Valentinianus Augustus\n| succession      =[[Roman Emperor|Emperor of the Roman Empire]]\n| image           = Valentiniano Primo.jpg\n| caption         = Valentinian I\n| reign           = 26 February{{snd}}28 March 364 (whole empire);<br>26 March 364{{snd}}17 November 375 (emperor of the [[Western Roman Empire|west]])\n| predecessor     = [[Jovian (Emperor)|Jovian]]\n| successor       = [[Valens]], [[Gratian]] and [[Valentinian II]]\n| spouse 1        = [[Marina Severa]]\n| spouse 2        = [[Justina (empress)|Justina]]\n| issue           = [[Gratian]] <br>[[Valentinian II]]<br> [[Galla (wife of Theodosius I)|Galla]]<br> Grata <br> Justa\n| dynasty         = [[Valentinian dynasty|Valentinian]]\n| father          = [[Gratian the Elder]]\n| mother          = \n| religion        = [[Nicene Christianity]]\n| birth_date   = {{date of birth|321|7|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Cibalae]], [[Pannonia Secunda]] ([[Vinkovci]], present-day [[Croatia]])\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|375|11|17|321|7|3|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Brigetio]], [[Pannonia Valeria]] ([[Sz\u0151ny]], present-day [[Hungary]])\n| place of burial = \n| reg-type={{nowrap|Co-emperor}}|regent=[[Valens]] {{small|([[List of Byzantine Emperors|Eastern Emperor]])}}|title=[[Augustus (honorific)|Augustus]] of the [[Western Roman Empire]]}}\n\n'''Valentinian I''' ({{lang-la|Flavius Valentinianus Augustus}};<ref>In [[Classical Latin]], Valentinian's name would read as FLAVIVS VALENTINIANVS AVGVSTVS.</ref> {{lang-grc-gre|\u039f\u1f50\u03b1\u03bb\u03b5\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03b9\u03b1\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2}}; 3 July 321{{snd}}17 November 375), also known as '''Valentinian the Great''',<ref>Philip Schaff, ''A Select Library of the Nicene and post Nicene Fathers of the Christian Church, Volume 3''. Eerdmans Publishing, University of California, 1956. p 146</ref><ref>Edward Kenneth Rand, ''Founders of the Middle Ages''. Dover Publications, University of Michigan, 1957. p 76</ref><ref>Michael Whitby, Mary Whitby, ''Chronicon Paschale 284\u2013628 AD''. Liverpool University Press, University of Michigan, 1989. p 51, 53</ref><ref>Gilbert Dagron, ''Emperor and priest: the imperial office in Byzantium''. Cambridge University Press, 2003. p 26</ref> was [[Roman emperor]] from 364 to 375. Upon becoming emperor he made his brother [[Valens]] his co-emperor, giving him rule of the [[Eastern Roman Empire|eastern provinces]] while Valentinian retained the [[Western Roman Empire|west]].\n\nDuring his reign, Valentinian fought successfully against the [[Alamanni]], [[Quadi]], and [[Sarmatians]]. Most notable was his victory over the Alamanni in 367 at the [[Battle of Solicinium]]. His brilliant general [[Count Theodosius]] defeated a revolt in [[Africa (Roman province)|Africa]] and the [[Great Conspiracy]], a coordinated assault on [[Roman Britain]] by [[Picts]], [[Scottish people|Scots]], and [[Saxons]]. Valentinian was also the last emperor to conduct campaigns across both the [[Rhine]] and [[Danube]] rivers. Valentinian rebuilt and improved the fortifications along the frontiers, even building fortresses in enemy territory.\n\nDue to the successful nature of his reign and the rapid decline of the empire after his death, he is often considered to be the \"last great western emperor\". He founded the [[Valentinian Dynasty]], with his sons [[Gratian]] and [[Valentinian II]] succeeding him in the western half of the empire.\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Solidus de Valentinien MAN.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Solidus of emperor Valentinian I.]]\nValentinian was born in 321<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXX.6.6</ref> at [[Cibalae]] in southern [[Pannonia]] (now [[Vinkovci]] in [[Croatia]]) into an [[Illyro-Romans|Illyro-Roman]] family.<ref name=\"Lenski2002\">{{cite book|last=Lenski|first=Noel Emmanuel|title=Failure of empire: Valens and the Roman state in the fourth century A.D.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uvXo39xOV8kC&pg=PA56|accessdate=12 October 2010|year=2002|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-23332-4|page=56}}</ref> Valentinian and his younger brother [[Valens]] were the sons of [[Gratian the Elder|Gratianus Major]], a prominent commander during the reigns of emperors [[Constantine the Great|Constantine I]] and [[Constans I]].<ref name=tomlinp2>{{cite book |author=Tomlin, R. |title=The Emperor Valentinian I |year=1973 |page=2}}</ref> He and his brother grew up on the family estate where they were educated in a variety of subjects, including painting and sculpting.<ref>Aurelius Victor, ''Epitome de Caesaribus''. 45.5</ref>\n\nGratian the Elder was promoted to ''[[Comes]] Africae'' in the late 320s or early 330s, and the young Valentinian accompanied his father to Africa.<ref name=tomlinp4>{{cite book |author=Tomlin, R. |title=The Emperor Valentinian I |year=1973 |page=4}}</ref> However, Gratian was soon accused of embezzlement and was forced to retire.<ref name=tomlinp4 /> Valentinian joined the army in the late 330s and later probably acquired the position of ''[[Domesticus (Roman Empire)|protector domesticus]]''.<ref name=tomlinp4 /> Gratian was later recalled during the early 340s and was made ''comes'' of [[Roman Britain|Britannia]].<ref name=tomlinp4 /> After holding this post, Gratianus retired to the family estate in Cibalae.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXX.7.3</ref>\n\nIn 350, Constans I was assassinated by agents of the [[usurper]] [[Magnentius]], a commander in [[Gaul]] proclaimed emperor by his soldiers.{{cn|date=August 2018}} [[Constantius II]], older brother of Constans and emperor in the East, promptly set forth towards Magnentius with a large army.<ref name=\"Zosimus, New History II.60\">Zosimus, ''New History'' II.60</ref> The following year the two emperors met in Pannonia. The ensuing [[Battle of Mursa Major]] resulted in a costly victory for Constantius.<ref>[[Joannes Zonaras|Zonaras]], ''Extracts of History'' XIII.8.5\u201313</ref> Two years later he defeated Magnentius again in southern Gaul at the [[Battle of Mons Seleucus]].<ref>[[Eutropius (historian)|Eutropius]], ''Historiae Romanae Breviarium'' X.11-2</ref> Magnentius, now realizing the futility of continuing his revolt, committed suicide in August that year; making Constantius sole ruler of the empire.<ref>[[Eutropius (historian)|Eutropius]], ''Historiae Romanae Breviarium'' X.12</ref> It was around this time that Constantius confiscated Gratianus' property, for supposedly showing hospitality to Magnentius when he was in Pannonia.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> Despite his father's fall from favor, Valentinian does not seem to have been adversely affected at this time, making it unlikely he ever fought for the usurper.<ref name=tomlinp13 /> It is known that Valentinian was in the region during the conflict, but what involvement he had in the war, if any, is unknown.<ref name=tomlinp13>{{cite book |author=Tomlin, R. |title=The Emperor Valentinian I |year=1973 |page=13}}</ref>\n\n==Service under Constantius and Julian==\nThe conflict between Magnentius and Constantius had allowed the [[Alamanni]] and [[Franks]] to take advantage of the confusion and cross the [[Rhine]], attacking several important settlements and fortifications.<ref name=\"tomlinp4\"/><ref name=tomlinp13 /> In 355, after deposing his cousin Gallus but still feeling the crises of the empire too much for one emperor to handle, Constantius raised his cousin [[Julian the Apostate|Julian]] to the rank of ''Caesar''.<ref name=tomlinp4 /> With the situation in Gaul rapidly deteriorating, Julian was made at least nominal commander of one of the two main armies in Gaul, [[Barbatio]] being commander of the other.<ref name=tomlinp4 /> Constantius devised a strategy where Julian and Barbatio would operate in a pincer movement against the Alamanni.<ref name=tomlinp13 /> However, a band of Alamanni slipped past Julian and Barbatio and attacked [[Lugdunum]] ([[Lyon]]). Julian sent the tribunes Valentinian and [[Bainobaudes]] to watch the road the raiders would have to return by. However, their efforts were hindered by Barbatio and his tribune [[Cella (soldier)|Cella]]. The Alamanni king [[Chnodomarius]] took advantage of the situation and attacked the Romans in detail, inflicting heavy losses.<ref name=tomlinp13 /> Barbatio complained to Constantius and the debacle was blamed on Valentinian and Bainobaudes, who were cashiered from the army.<ref name=tomlinp13 />\n\nWith his career in ruins, Valentinian returned to his new family estate in [[Sirmium]]. Two years later his first son [[Gratian]] was born by his wife [[Marina Severa]].<ref name=tomlinp14>{{cite book |author=Tomlin, R. |title=The Emperor Valentinian I |year=1973 |page=14}}</ref> Valentinian's actions and location become uncertain around this time, but he was likely exiled.<ref>Sources give different commands Valentinian held at the time and vastly different places of exile: [[Philostorgius]] says Constantius exiled Valentinian to [[Thebes, Egypt|Thebes]] in [[Roman Egypt|Egypt]], [[Sosomen]] to [[Melitene]] in [[Lesser Armenia|Armenia]], the [[Paschal Chronicle]] to [[Selymbria]] in [[Thrace]], and [[Theodoret]] to \"a distant fort\". Tomlin, p. 14.</ref> Theodoret say that this was because he'd reacted angrily when a pagan temple attendant sprinkled water on him, saying \"I am not purified, but defiled\", and striking the priest.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gaddis |first1=Michael |title=There Is No Crime for Those Who Have Christ: Religious Violence in the Christian Roman Empire |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0520286245 |page=256 |url=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=iaowDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA256&lpg=PA256&dq=Valentinian+exiled+defile&source=bl&ots=okX_hhqUVR&sig=ACfU3U0FWUFQcdFE2Mb7FIjNyWN0yYmhPQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjG0tLU-ZPgAhUWVH0KHXpUAtQQ6AEwAHoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=Valentinian%20exiled%20defile&f=false |accessdate=29 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Rise to power==\nAt the news of Julian's death on a campaign against the Sassanids, the army hastily declared a commander, [[Jovian (Emperor)|Jovian]], emperor. The army still found itself beleaguered by Persian attacks, forcing Jovian to accept humiliating peace terms.<ref name=tomlinp16>{{cite book |author=Tomlin, R. |title=The Emperor Valentinian I |year=1973 |page=16}}</ref> Jovian's authority within the empire was still insecure, so he sent a notary [[Procopius (notary)|Procopius]] and the tribune [[Memoridus]] west to announce his accession.<ref name=tomlinp16 /> During Jovian's reign Valentinian was promoted to tribune of a ''Scutarii'' (elite infantry) regiment, and was dispatched to Ancyra. Jovian's rule would be short \u2013 only eight months \u2013 and before he could even consolidate his position in [[Constantinople]] he died en route between [[Ancyra]] and [[Nicaea]]. His death was attributed to either assassination by poisoning or accidental carbon monoxide poisoning. Jovian is remembered mostly for restoring Christianity to its previous favored status under Constantine and his sons.\n\nThe army marched to Nicaea, and a meeting of civil and military officials was convened to choose a new emperor. The purple was offered to [[Sallustius]], who had refused it once before on Julian's death. The prefect declined, and did so again on behalf of his son when the offer was extended to him.<ref>[[Edward Gibbon]], ''The Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire'', (The Modern Library, 1932), ch. XXV., pp. 845, 846</ref> Two different names were proposed: [[Aequitius]], a tribune of the first Scutarii, and Januarius, a relative of Jovian's in charge of military supplies in Illyricum. Both were rejected; Aequitius as too rough and boorish,<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVI.1.4</ref> Januarius because he was too far away.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVI.1.5</ref> As a man well qualified and at hand, the assembly finally agreed upon Valentinian,  and sent messengers to inform him in Ancyra.\n\n==Emperor==\n{{Refimprove section|date=February 2017}}\nValentinian accepted the acclamation on 26 February 364. As he prepared to make his accession speech the soldiers threatened to riot, apparently uncertain as to where his loyalties lay. Valentinian reassured them that the army was his greatest priority. According to Ammianus the soldiers were astounded by Valentinian\u2019s bold demeanor and his willingness to assume the imperial authority. To further prevent a succession crisis he agreed to pick a co-Augustus. His decision to elect a fellow-emperor could also be construed as a move to appease any opposition among the civilian officials in the eastern portion of the Empire. By agreeing to appoint a co-ruler, he assured the eastern officials that someone with imperial authority would remain in the east to protect their interests.\n\nValentinian selected his brother Valens as co-Augustus at Constantinople on 28 March 364. This was done over the objections of [[Dagalaifus (Roman Consul, 366)|Dagalaifus]], the ''[[magister equitum]]''. Ammianus makes it clear that Valens was subordinate to his brother. The remainder of 364 was spent delegating administrative duties and military commands. According to the 5th century historian [[Zosimus]], who as a [[Pagan]] was inclined to revile the restorer of [[Christianity]], all the ministers and officials appointed by Julian were summarily dismissed in disgrace; modern authorities have qualified the assertion.<ref>Gibbon, p. 849 note</ref> It is certain that some reshuffling of commands occurred along with the division of the provinces, but the changes were strictly based on merit. The [[Sophists]] and philosophers who had proliferated in the court of the apostate, drawing large salaries for delusive services, were cashiered.<ref>Gibbon, ch. XXIII., pp. 771-73; ch. XXV., p. 849</ref>  Valentinian retained the services of Dagalaifus and promoted Aequitius to ''Comes Illyricum''. Valens was given the [[Prefecture of Oriens]], governed by [[prefect]] [[Salutius]]. Valentinian gained control of [[Praetorian prefecture of Italy|Italy]], [[Prefecture of Gaul|Gaul]], [[Praetorian prefecture of Africa|Africa]], and [[Prefecture of Illyricum|Illyricum]]. Valens resided in [[Constantinople]], while Valentinian\u2019s court was at [[Mediolanum]].\n\n===Campaigns in Gaul and Germania===\n[[File:Colosso-de-barletta.jpg|thumb|upright|The emperor depicted in the [[Colossus of Barletta]] could very well be Valentinian I.<ref>Cunliffe B. W. (1994) ''Rome and Her Empire'', Constable, p. 317</ref>]]\n\nIn 365 the [[Alamanni]] crossed the Rhine and invaded Gaul. Simultaneously, [[Procopius (usurper)|Procopius]] \u2013 the last scion of the [[Constantinian dynasty]] \u2013 began his revolt against Valens in the east. According to Ammianus, Valentinian received news of both the Alamanni and Procopius' revolt on 1 November while on his way to [[Paris]]. He initially sent Dagalaifus to fight the Alamanni<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVI.5.9</ref> while he himself made preparations to march east and help Valens. After receiving counsel from his court and deputations from the leading Gallic cities begging him to stay and protect Gaul, he decided to remain in Gaul and fight the Alamanni.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVI.5.12</ref><ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVI.5.13</ref>\nValentinian advanced to [[Durocortorum]] and sent two generals, Charietto and Severianus, against the invaders.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVII.1.2</ref> Both generals were promptly defeated and killed.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVII.1.4</ref> In 366, Dagalaifus was sent against the Alamanni but he was also ineffective.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVII.2.1</ref> Late in the campaigning season Dagalaifus was replaced by Jovinus, a general from the court of Valentinian. After several victories along the [[Meuse river]] Jovinus pushed the Alamanni out of Gaul and was awarded the consulate the following year for his efforts.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVII.2.10</ref>\n\nIn early 367 Valentinian was distracted from launching a punitive expedition against the Alamanni due to crises in Britain and northern Gaul. The Alamanni promptly re-crossed the Rhine and plundered [[Moguntiacum]]. Valentinian succeeded in arranging the assassination of [[Vithicabius]], an Alamannic leader, but Valentinian was more determined to bring the Alamanni under Roman hegemony. Valentinian spent the entire winter of 367 gathering a massive army for a spring offensive. He summoned the ''Comes Italiae'' Sebastianus, with the Italian and Illyrian legions, to join Jovinus and Severus, the ''[[magister peditum]]''. In the spring of 368 Valentinian, his eight-year-old son Gratian and the army crossed the Rhine and [[Main (river)|Main]] rivers into Alamannic territory. They did not encounter any resistance initially \u2013 burning any dwellings or food stores they found along the way. Finally, Valentinian fought the Alamanni in the [[Battle of Solicinium]]; the Romans were victorious<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVII.10.15</ref> but suffered heavy casualties.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVII.10.16</ref> A temporary peace was reached and Valentinian returned to [[Trier]] for the winter.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVII.10.17</ref> During 369, Valentinian ordered new defensive works to be constructed and old structures refurbished along the length of the Rhine\u2019s west bank.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVIII.2.1</ref> Boldly, he ordered the construction of a fortress across the Rhine in the mountains near modern [[Heidelberg]].<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVIII.2.2</ref> The Alamanni sent envoys to protest, but they were dismissed. The Alamanni attacked the fortress while it was still under construction and destroyed it.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXVIII.2.8</ref>\n\nIn 370 the [[Saxons]] renewed their attacks on northern Gaul. Nannienus, the ''comes'' in charge of the troops in northern Gaul, urged Severus to come to his aid. After several modest successes, a truce was called and the Saxons handed over to the Romans young men fit for duty in the Roman military \u2013 in exchange for free passage back to their homeland. The Romans ambushed them and destroyed the entire invading force.<ref>Rike, R.L., ''Apex Omnium: Religion in the Res Gestae of Ammianus'' (1987), pg. 91; Jones, Martindale and Morris, ''The Prosopography of the Later Roman Empire'' Vol. I (1971), pgs. 615-616</ref>\n\nValentinian meanwhile tried to persuade the [[Burgundians]] \u2013 bitter enemies of the Alamanni \u2013 to attack [[Macrian]], a powerful Alamannic chieftain. If the Alamanni tried to flee, Valentinian would be waiting for them with his army. Negotiations with the Burgundians broke down when Valentinian, in his usual high-handed manner, refused to meet with the Burgundian envoys and personally assure them of Roman support. Nevertheless, rumors of a Roman alliance with the Burgundians did have the effect of scattering the Alamanni through fear of an imminent attack from their enemies. This event allowed the ''[[magister equitum]]'' [[Count Theodosius|Theodosius]] to attack the Alamanni through Raetia \u2013 taking many Alamannic prisoners. These captured Alamanni were settled in the [[Po river]] valley in Italy, where they were still settled at the time Ammianus wrote his history.\n\nValentinian campaigned unsuccessfully for four more years to defeat Macrian who in 372 barely escaped capture by Theodosius. Meanwhile, Valentinian continued to recruit heavily from Alamanni friendly to Rome. He sent the Alamannic king Fraomarius, as a Tribune, to Britain in 372-373 with an army in order to replenish troops there and made the noblemen Bitheridius and [[Hortarius]] commanders in his army although Hortarius was soon executed for conspiring with Macrian. Valentinian\u2019s Alamannic campaigns, however, were hampered by troubles first in Africa, and later on the Danube river. In 374 Valentinian was forced to make peace with Macrian because the Emperor's presence was needed to counter an invasion of Illyricum by the Quadi and Sarmatians.\n\n===The Great Conspiracy===\nIn 367, Valentinian received reports from Britain that a combined force of [[Picts]], [[Attacotti]] and [[Scoti|Scots]] had killed the ''[[Comes litoris Saxonici]]'' [[Nectaridus]] and ''[[Dux Britanniarum]]'' [[Fullofaudes]]. At the same time, Frankish and Saxon forces were raiding the coastal areas of northern Gaul. The empire was in the midst of the [[Great Conspiracy]] \u2013 and was in danger of losing control of Britain altogether. Valentinian set out for Britain, sending ''Comes domesticorum'' Severus ahead of him to investigate. Severus was not able to correct the situation and returned to Gaul, meeting Valentinian at [[Samarobriva]]. Valentinian then sent Jovinus to Britain and promoted Severus to magister peditum. It was at this time that Valentinian fell ill and a battle for succession broke out between Severus, a representative of the army, and Rusticus Julianus, ''magister memoriae'' and a representative of the Gallic nobility. Valentinian soon recovered however and appointed his son Gratian as his co-Augustus in the west. Ammianus remarks that such an action was unprecedented. Jovinus quickly returned saying that he needed more men to take care of the situation. In 368 Valentinian appointed Theodosius as the new ''[[Comes Britanniarum]]'' with instructions to return Britain to Roman rule. Meanwhile, Severus and Jovinus were to accompany the emperor on his campaign against the Alamanni.\n\nTheodosius arrived in 368 with the [[Batavi (Germanic tribe)|Batavi]], [[Heruli]], Jovii and Victores legions. Landing at [[Rutupi\u00e6]], he proceeded to [[Londinium]] restoring order to southern Britain. Later, he rallied the remaining garrison which was originally stationed in Britain; it was apparent the units had lost their cohesiveness when Fullofaudes and Nectaridus had been defeated. Theodosius sent for [[Civilis (vicarius)|Civilis]] to be installed as the new [[vicarius]] of the [[diocese]] and [[Dulcitius]] as an additional general.\nIn 369, Theodosius set about reconquering the areas north of [[London]]; putting down the revolt of [[Valentinus (rebel)|Valentinus]], the brother-in-law of a [[vicarius]], [[Maximinus (praetorian prefect)|Maximinus]]. Subsequently, Theodosius restored the rest of Britain to the empire and rebuilt many fortifications \u2013 renaming northern Britain '[[Valentia (Roman Britain)|Valentia]]'. After his return in 369, Valentinian promoted Theodosius to ''magister equitum'' in place of Jovinus.\n\n===Revolt in Africa and crises on the Danube===\n[[File:Missorio di valentiniano I, argento, 364-75 ca., dall'arve, 02.JPG|thumb|right|Silver missorium (heavily worn) believed to depict Valentinian I. The armoured and haloed emperor is flanked by infantry soldiers, he holds a [[labarum]] in one hand and an orb surmounted by a figure of Victory in the other, ca. 364-375]]\nIn 372, the rebellion of [[Firmus (4th century usurper)|Firmus]] broke out in the still-devastated African provinces. This rebellion was driven by the corruption of the ''comes'' Romanus. Romanus took sides in the murderous disputes among the legitimate and illegitimate children of Nubel, a Moorish prince and leading Roman client in Africa. Resentment of Romanus' peculations and his failure to defend the province from desert nomads caused some of the provincials to revolt. Valentinian                   sent in Theodosius to restore imperial control. Over the following two years Theodosius uncovered Romanus' crimes, arrested him and his supporters, and defeated Firmus.\n\nIn 373, hostilities erupted with the [[Quadi]], a group of Germanic-speaking people living on the upper Danube. Like the Alamanni, the Quadi were outraged that Valentinian was building fortifications in their territory. They complained and sent deputations to the ''magister armorum per Illyricum'' Aequitius, who promised to refer the matter to Valentinian. However, the increasingly influential minister Maximinus, now praetorian prefect of Gaul, blamed Aequitius to Valentinian for the trouble, and managed to have him promote his son Marcellianus to finish the project.<ref>Gibbon, p. 894</ref> The protests of Quadic leaders continued to delay the project, and to put an end to their clamor Marcellianus murdered the Quadic king [[Gabinius (king)|Gabinius]] at a banquet ostensibly arranged for peaceful negotiations. This roused the Quadi to war, along with their allies the Sarmatians. During the fall, they crossed the Danube and began ravaging the province of [[Pannonia Valeria]]. The marauders could not penetrate the fortified cities, but they heavily damaged the unprotected countryside. Two legions were sent in but failed to coordinate and were routed by the Sarmatians. Meanwhile, another group of Sarmatians invaded [[Moesia]], but were driven back by the son of Theodosius, ''Dux Moesiae'' and later emperor [[Theodosius I|Theodosius]].\n\nValentinian did not receive news of these crises until late 374. The following spring he set out from Trier and arrived at [[Carnuntum]], which was deserted. There he was met by Sarmatian envoys who begged forgiveness for their actions. Valentinian replied that he would investigate what had happened and act accordingly. Valentinian ignored Marcellianus\u2019 treacherous actions and decided to punish the Quadi. He was accompanied by Sebastianus and [[Merobaudes (general)|Merobaudes]], and spent the summer months preparing for the campaign. In the fall he crossed the Danube at [[Aquincum]] into Quadi territory.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXX.5.13</ref> After pillaging Quadi lands without opposition, he retired to [[Sabaria|Savaria]] to winter quarters.<ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, ''Res Gestae'' XXX.5.14</ref>\n\n====Death====\nWithout waiting for the spring he decided to continue campaigning and moved from Savaria to [[Szony|Brigetio]]. Once he arrived on 17 November, he received a deputation from the Quadi. In return for supplying fresh recruits to the Roman army, the Quadi were to be allowed to leave in peace. However, before the envoys left they were granted an audience with Valentinian. The envoys insisted that the conflict was caused by the building of Roman forts in their lands; furthermore individual bands of Quadi were not necessarily bound to the rule of the chiefs who had made treaties with the Romans \u2013 and thus might attack the Romans at any time. The attitude of the envoys so enraged Valentinian that he suffered a burst blood vessel in the skull while angrily yelling at them, provoking his death<ref>{{cite book|last=Gibbon|first=Edward|title=The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire: Edited in Seven Volumes with Introduction, Notes, Appendices, and Index|date=2012|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781108050739|page=66|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zgtcg0nMg_IC&pg=PA66}}</ref> on November 17, 375.\n\n== Reputation ==\n[[A.H.M. Jones]] writes that although Valentinian I was \"less of a boor\" than his chief rival for election to the imperial throne, \"he was of a violent and brutal temper, and not only uncultivated himself, but hostile to cultivated persons\". According to [[Ammianus Marcellinus|Ammianus]], \"he hated the well-dressed and educated and wealthy and well-born\". He was, however, an able soldier and a conscientious administrator, and took an interest in the welfare of the humbler classes, from which his father had risen. Unfortunately his good intentions were often frustrated by a bad choice of ministers, and \"an obstinate belief in their merits despite all evidence to the contrary.\"<ref>A.H.M. Jones, ''The Later Roman Empire, 284\u2013602: A Social, Economic and Administrative Survey'' (Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University, 1986), p. 139.</ref> He was a founder of schools, and provided medical attendance for the poor of [[Rome]], by appointing a physician for each of the fourteen districts of the city.<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Valentinian I.|volume=27|page=851}}</ref> He also reissued an edict of [[Constantine I]] making infanticide a capital offence.<ref>Gibbon, ch. XIV., p. 375; ch. XXV., p. 859</ref>\n\nNotwithstanding the benevolence of these more generous edicts, Valentinian was remarkable for cruelty and barbarism in his private affairs.\nHe often had servants and attendants executed on trifling charges, and was reportedly accustomed to keep two bears, known as ''Micca Aurea'' (''golden camel''), and ''Innocence'', in an iron cage which was transported wherever he went, whom he employed to execute the sentence, which he often delivered, of capital punishment. At length ''Innocence'', when she was considered to have faithfully discharged her office, was released with the emperor's good wishes into her native wilds.<ref>[[Charles Kingsley]], ''The Roman And The Teuton, A Series Of Lectures delivered before the University of Cambridge'', (Macmillan And Co., 1889, London), lecture II, ''The Dying Empire''</ref>\n\nValentinian was a [[Christians|Christian]] but permitted liberal religious freedom to all his subjects, proscribing only some forms of rituals such as particular types of sacrifices, and banning the practice of magic. Again, Valentinian steadily set his face against the increasing wealth and worldliness of the clergy. He issued a pointed edict via [[Pope Damasus I]], forbidding the grant of bequests to Christian clergy-men; and another forcing members of the sacerdotal order to discharge the public duties owed on account of their property, or else relinquish it.<ref>Gibbon, ch. XXV., p. 864; ch. XX., p. 662, editor's note</ref><ref name=\"EB1911\"/>\n\n[[Socrates of Constantinople|Socrates Scholasticus]] gives an interesting account in his Historia Ecclesiastica of Valentinian's marriages, that has inspired some to call this emperor [[Polygamy in Christianity|polygamous]]. According to the text: the empress [[Justina (empress)|Justina]] \"became known to [[Marina Severa]], wife of the emperor Valentinian, and had frequent dialogue with the empress, until their intimacy at length grew to such an extent that they were accustomed to bathe together. When Severa saw Justina in the bath she was greatly struck with the beauty of the virgin, and spoke of her to the emperor; saying that the daughter of Justus was so lovely a creature, and possessed of such symmetry of form, that she herself, though a woman, was altogether charmed with her. The emperor, treasuring this description by his wife in his own mind, considered with himself how he could espouse Justina, without repudiating Severa, as she had borne him Gratian, whom he had created Augustus a little while before. He accordingly framed a law, and caused it to be published throughout all the cities, by which any man was permitted to have two lawful wives. The law was promulgated and he married Justina, by whom he had Valentinian the younger.\" (Book IV, chapt. 31.)<ref>Translated by A.C. Zenos. From Nicene and Post-Nicene Fathers, Second Series, Vol. 2. Edited by Philip Schaff and Henry Wace. (Buffalo, NY: Christian Literature Publishing Co., 1890.)</ref>\n\nThis story is only known from Socrates and no trace of any edict by any emperor allowing polygamy exists. Valentinian I may have divorced Severa according to Roman Law, which allowed for divorce (see [[Women in Ancient Rome]]).<ref>Frier, Bruce W. and McGinn, Thomas A.J.: A Casebook on Roman Family Law (American Philological Association) OUP USA 2003. Part D, The End of Marriage</ref> However, since divorce was not acknowledged by Christians,<ref>Matthew 19, 4\u20136.</ref> Socrates contemptuously describes him as a bigamist. It is also possible that Socrates attempted to accuse Justina, who was an [[Arianism|Arian]], of fornication, a common aspersion against other cults. According to [[John Malalas]], the [[Chronicon Paschale]], and [[John of Nikiu]], the empress Severa was banished by Valentinian I for conducting an illegal transaction, before he consorted with Justina. Barnes believes this story to be an attempt to justify the divorce of Valentinian I without accusing the emperor.<ref>Timothy Barnes, \"Ammianus Marcellinus and the Representation of Historical Reality\" (1998), p. 123\u2013125</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Byzantine Empire}}\n*[[List of Byzantine emperors]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n===Primary sources===\n*Ammianus Marcellinus. Rerum gestarum libri qui supersunt. W. Seyfarth, ed. 3 vols. Leipzig, 1978.\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Charles|first=Robert H.|authorlink=Robert Charles (scholar)|title=The Chronicle of John, Bishop of Nikiu: Translated from Zotenberg's Ethiopic Text|year=2007|origyear=1916|location=Merchantville, NJ|publisher=Evolution Publishing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KgZ-DOr77OQC}}\n*Consularia Constantinopolitana. T. Mommsen ed., Monumenta Germaniae Historica, Auctores Antiquissimi. Volume 9. Berlin, 1892.\n*Codex Theodosianus. T. Mommsen, P.M. Meyer, and P. Kr\u00fcger, eds. Theodosiani libri XVI cum constitutionibus Sirmondianis et leges novellae ad Theodosianum pertinentes (2 vols.). Berlin, 1905.\n*Corpus Inscriptionum Latinarum. Vol. 6. T. Mommsen, ed. Berlin, 1875.\n*Epitome de Caesaribus. F.R. Pichlmayr, ed. Leipzig, 1961.\n*Jerome. Chronicon. R. Helm, ed., in Malcolm Drew Donalson, A Translation of Jerome\u2019s Chronicon with Historical Commentary. Lewiston, NY, 1996.\n*Orosius. Adversus paganos historiarum libri septem. Z. Zangemeister, ed. Corpus scriptorum ecclesiasticorum latinorum 5. Vienna, 1882.\n*Socrates. Historia Ecclesiastica. J.P. Migne ed., Patrologia Graeca 67. Paris, 1864.\n*Sozomen. Historia Ecclesiastica. J.P. Migne ed., Patrologia Graeca 67. Paris, 1864.\n*Theoderet. Historia Ecclesiastica. J.P. Migne ed., Patrologia Graeca 82. Paris, 1864.\n*Zosimus. Historia nova. Fran\u00e7ois Paschoud, ed. and trans., Zosime: Histoire Nouvelle (3 vols.). Paris, 1971\u201389.\n*Ammian, Books&nbsp;26\u201130 [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/home.html#26 Uchicago.edu]. English summaries. Main text in Latin.\n\n===Secondary accounts===\n* [http://www.roman-emperors.org/vali.htm ''De Imperatoribus Romanis''] English text.\n* [[Edward Gibbon]], ''The Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire'', 1776.\n* M. Grant, ''The Roman Emperors'', 1985.\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle = Valentinian I.|volume=27 |page=851}} <!-- Unusually, we cite EB1911 in two ways, because its body contains an alternative summary of the biography, and also some specific attributions (see the references secction) -->\n* {{in lang|de}} Schmidt-Hofner, Sebastian. ''Reagieren und Gestalten: der Regierungsstil des spaetroemischen Kaisers am Beispiel der Gesetzgebung Valentinians I''. Muenchen: Beck, 2008. 398 p. (Vestigia, Bd. 58).\n* [[Ernst Stein]], ''Histoire du Bas-Empire,'' vol. i, chap. 4 (1959).\n* {{cite CE1913|wstitle = Valentinian|volume=16}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons}}\n* This [http://www.fourthcentury.com/index.php/imperial-laws-chart-364 list of Roman laws of the fourth century] shows laws passed by Valentinian I relating to Christianity.\n\t\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Valentinian dynasty]]||321|17 November|375}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Jovian (Emperor)|Jovian]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[List of Roman Emperors|Roman Emperor]]\n        | years=364\u2013375\n        | alongside=[[Valens]] }}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Valens]], [[Gratian]] and [[Valentinian II]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef | before= [[Jovian (Emperor)|Jovian]],<br />[[Varronianus (son of Jovian)|Varronianus]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[List of Roman Consuls|Consul]] of the [[Roman Empire]] | years=365 |regent1= [[Valens]]}}\n{{s-aft | after= [[Gratian]],<br />Dagalaifus}}\n{{s-bef | before= [[Flavius Lupicinus (consul 367)|Flavius Lupicinus]],<br />Flavius Iovinus}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[List of Roman Consuls|Consul]] of the [[Roman Empire]] | years=368 |regent1= [[Valens]]}}\n{{s-aft | after= [[Valentinianus 